dros L. Zaous\u0113s|title=Ho empaigmos: 21 Apriliou 1967-24 Iouliou 1974|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=N0toAAAAMAAJ&q=%CE%94%CE%B9%CE%BF%CE%BC%CE%AE%CE%B4%CE%B7%CF%82+%CE%9A%CE%BF%CE%BC%CE%BD%CE%B7%CE%BD%CF%8C%CF%82&dq=%CE%94%CE%B9%CE%BF%CE%BC%CE%AE%CE%B4%CE%B7%CF%82+%CE%9A%CE%BF%CE%BC%CE%BD%CE%B7%CE%BD%CF%8C%CF%82&hl=en&sa=X&ei=bjzYUaeELoKlrAGa7IHIDA&ved=0CFsQ6AEwBw|accessdate=6 July 2013|year=1998|publisher=Ekdoseis Papaz\u0113s\u0113|page=229|quote=\u0395\u03c0\u03af\u03c3\u03b7\u03c2 \u03ad\u03c7\u03b5\u03b9 \u03c5\u03c0\u03bf\u03c3\u03c4\u03b7\u03c1\u03b9\u03c7\u03b8\u03b5\u03af \u03cc\u03c4\u03b9 \u03bf\u03c5\u03c3\u03b9\u03b1\u03c3\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03ac \u03bf \u03bc\u03cc\u03bd\u03bf\u03c2 \u03bd\u03b5\u03ba\u03c1\u03cc\u03c2 \u03bc\u03c0\u03c1\u03bf\u03c3\u03c4\u03ac \u03c3\u03c4\u03bf \u03a0\u03bf\u03bb\u03c5\u03c4\u03b5\u03c7\u03bd\u03b5\u03af\u03bf \u03ae\u03c4\u03b1\u03bd \u03bf \u03ac\u03c4\u03c5\u03c7\u03bf\u03c2 \u03ad\u03c6\u03b7\u03b2\u03bf\u03c2 \u03bc\u03b1\u03b8\u03b7\u03c4\u03ae\u03c2, \u03bf \u0394\u03b9\u03bf\u03bc\u03ae\u03b4\u03b7\u03c2 \u039a\u03bf\u03bc\u03bd\u03b7\u03bd\u03cc\u03c2.}}</ref> He was shot opposite the main gate of the Polytechnic.<ref name=\"Chatz\u0113s\u014dkrat\u0113s2004\">{{cite book|author=D\u0113m\u0113tr\u0113s Chatz\u0113s\u014dkrat\u0113s|title=\u03a0\u03bf\u03bb\u03c5\u03c4\u03b5\u03a7\u03bd\u03b5\u03b9\u03bf '73: \u0391\u03bd\u03b1\u03c3\u03c4\u03bf\u03a7\u03b1\u03c3\u03bc\u03bf\u03c2 \u03bc\u03b9\u03b1\u03c2 \u03c0\u03c1\u03b1\u03b3\u03bc\u03b1\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03bf\u03c4\u03b7\u03c4\u03b1\u03c2|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Z5cOAQAAMAAJ&q=%CE%94%CE%B9%CE%BF%CE%BC%CE%AE%CE%B4%CE%B7%CF%82+%CE%9A%CE%BF%CE%BC%CE%BD%CE%B7%CE%BD%CF%8C%CF%82&dq=%CE%94%CE%B9%CE%BF%CE%BC%CE%AE%CE%B4%CE%B7%CF%82+%CE%9A%CE%BF%CE%BC%CE%BD%CE%B7%CE%BD%CF%8C%CF%82&hl=en&sa=X&ei=bjzYUaeELoKlrAGa7IHIDA&ved=0CEgQ6AEwBA|accessdate=6 July 2013|year=2004|publisher=\u03a0\u03bf\u03bb\u03b9\u03c2|isbn=978-960-435-013-1|page=142|quote=10:15 \u03bc.\u03bc. \u039f \u03c0\u03c1\u03ce\u03c4\u03bf\u03c2 \u03bd\u03b5\u03ba\u03c1\u03cc\u03c2 \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5 \u03a0\u03bf\u03bb\u03c5\u03c4\u03b5\u03c7\u03bd\u03b5\u03af\u03bf\u03c5. \u039f \u03b4\u03b5\u03ba\u03b1\u03b5\u03c6\u03c4\u03ac\u03c7\u03c1\u03bf\u03bd\u03bf\u03c2 \u03bc\u03b1\u03b8\u03b7\u03c4\u03ae\u03c2 \u0394\u03b9\u03bf\u03bc\u03ae\u03b4\u03b7\u03c2 \u039a\u03bf\u03bc\u03bd\u03b7\u03bd\u03cc\u03c2 \u03c0\u03c5\u03c1\u03bf\u03b2\u03bf\u03bb\u03b5\u03af\u03c4\u03b1\u03b9 \u03b8\u03b1\u03bd\u03ac\u03c3\u03b9\u03bc\u03b1 \u03c3\u03c4\u03b7\u03bd \u03a0\u03b1\u03c4\u03b7\u03c3\u03af\u03c9\u03bd \u03b1\u03c0\u03ad\u03bd\u03b1\u03bd\u03c4\u03b9 \u03b1\u03c0\u03cc \u03c4\u03b7\u03bd \u03ba\u03b5\u03bd\u03c4\u03c1\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae \u03c0\u03cd\u03bb\u03b7.}}</ref>\n\n==The events==\nOn the night of Friday, November 16, 1973, police forces started confronting the thousands of protesters gathered inside and outside the Polytechnic campus, located on [[Patission Street]], one of the busiest in Athens. Komnenos was one of the many high school students barricaded inside the Polytechnic. At about 10:00 pm, the police used guns and smoke-bombs to evacuate the streets from the protesters. At the time, Komninos had joined other students on the corner of [[Tritis Septemvriou Street]] and Averof St.,<ref>Intersection coordinates: ({{coord|37|59|20|N|23|43|45|E|}})</ref> exactly across from the Polytechnic. It is reported that Komninos went from the student side to the middle of the street toward the police lines and raising his hands he told them from a distance of about forty metres: \"If you are men come and hit us from up close\".<ref name=\"Pliatsika-Pansel\u0113nou1976\">{{cite book|author=Eph\u0113 Pliatsika-Pansel\u0113nou|title=Katachtemene chora : mythistorema|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JQIKAQAAIAAJ&q=%22%CE%94%CE%B9%CE%BF%CE%BC%CE%AE%CE%B4%CE%B7%CF%82+%CE%9A%CE%BF%CE%BC%CE%BD%CE%B7%CE%BD%CF%8C%CF%82%22&dq=%22%CE%94%CE%B9%CE%BF%CE%BC%CE%AE%CE%B4%CE%B7%CF%82+%CE%9A%CE%BF%CE%BC%CE%BD%CE%B7%CE%BD%CF%8C%CF%82%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=W0fYUdgkyf6oAcrbgKgK&ved=0CC4Q6AEwAA|accessdate=6 July 2013|year=1976|publisher=Ekdoseis Synchrone epoche|pages=292\u2013294|quote=\u038c \u0394\u03b9\u03bf\u03bc\u03ae\u03b4\u03b7\u03c2 \u039a\u03bf\u03bc\u03bd\u03b7\u03bd\u03cc\u03c2, \u03b2\u03b3\u03ae\u03ba\u03b5 \u03be\u03b1\u03c6\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03ac \u03c3\u03c4\u03b7 \u03bc\u03ad\u03c3\u03b7 \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5 \u03b4\u03c1\u03cc\u03bc\u03bf\u03c5, \u03c3\u03ae\u03ba\u03c9\u03c3\u03b5 \u03c4\u03b1 \u03c7\u03ad\u03c1\u03b9\u03b1, \u03b2\u03bb\u03ad\u03c0\u03bf\u03bd\u03c4\u03b1\u03c2 \u03c0\u03c1\u03bf\u03c2 \u03c4\u03b7 \u03bc\u03b5\u03c1\u03b9\u03ac \u03c4\u03c9\u03bd \u03b1\u03c3\u03c4\u03c5\u03bd\u03bf\u03bc\u03b9\u03ba\u03ce\u03bd, \u03c0\u03bf\u03c5 \u03b2\u03c1\u03af\u03c3\u03ba\u03bf\u03bd\u03c4\u03b1\u03bd \u03c3\u03b5 \u03b1\u03c0\u03cc\u03c3\u03c4\u03b1\u03c3\u03b7 \u03c3\u03b1\u03c1\u03ac\u03bd\u03c4\u03b1 \u03c0\u03b5\u03c1\u03af\u03c0\u03bf\u03c5 \u03bc\u03ad\u03c4\u03c1\u03c9\u03bd \u03ba\u03b1\u03af \u03b5\u03af\u03c0\u03b5: \"\"\u0391\u03bd \u03b5\u03af\u03c3\u03b1\u03c3\u03c4\u03b5 \u03ac\u03bd\u03c4\u03c1\u03b5\u03c2, \u03b5\u03bb\u03ac\u03c4\u03b5 \u03bd\u03b1 \u03bc\u03b1\u03c2 \u03c7\u03c4\u03c5\u03c0\u03ae\u03c3\u03b5\u03c4\u03b5 \u03b1\u03c0\u03cc \u03ba\u03bf\u03bd\u03c4\u03ac.}}</ref> The students were reportedly hit by sniper fire from the roofs of the neighbouring buildings. Komnenos was killed at 10:15&nbsp;p.m. when a bullet pierced his heart.<ref name=\"Chatz\u0113s\u014dkrat\u0113s2004\"/><ref name=\"Panourgi\u00e11995\">{{cite book|author=Eleni Neni K. Panourgi\u00e1|title=Fragments of Death, Fables of Identity: An Athenian Anthropography|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mKJcA4Cj03gC&pg=PA145|accessdate=24 May 2012|year=1995|publisher=Univ of Wisconsin Press|isbn=978-0-299-14564-4|page=145}}</ref><ref name=\"Gatos2002\">{{cite book|author=Gi\u014drgos Gatos|title=Polytechneio '73: reportaz me t\u0113n historia : to chroniko, hoi martyries, ta \u1e0fokoumenta|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tOs0AAAAMAAJ&q=%CE%94%CE%B9%CE%BF%CE%BC%CE%AE%CE%B4%CE%B7%CF%82+%CE%9A%CE%BF%CE%BC%CE%BD%CE%B7%CE%BD%CF%8C%CF%82&dq=%CE%94%CE%B9%CE%BF%CE%BC%CE%AE%CE%B4%CE%B7%CF%82+%CE%9A%CE%BF%CE%BC%CE%BD%CE%B7%CE%BD%CF%8C%CF%82&hl=en&sa=X&ei=bjzYUaeELoKlrAGa7IHIDA&ved=0CEIQ6AEwAw|accessdate=6 July 2013|year=2002|publisher=Ekdoseis Philippot\u0113|page=52|quote=\u03a4\u03cc\u03c4\u03b5 \u03b1\u03ba\u03bf\u03cd\u03c3\u03c4\u03b7\u03ba\u03b1\u03bd \u03c0\u03c5\u03c1\u03bf\u03b2\u03bf\u03bb\u03b9\u03c3\u03bc\u03bf\u03af \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 \u03bf \u03bd\u03b5\u03b1\u03c1\u03cc\u03c2 \u03c0\u03bf\u03c5 \u03ae\u03c4\u03b1\u03bd \u03bf \u03bc\u03b1\u03b8\u03b7\u03c4\u03ae\u03c2 \u0394\u03b9\u03bf\u03bc\u03ae\u03b4\u03b7\u03c2 \u039a\u03bf\u03bc\u03bd\u03b7\u03bd\u03cc\u03c2, \u03ad\u03c0\u03b5\u03c3\u03b5 \u03c3\u03c4\u03bf \u03ad\u03b4\u03b1\u03c6\u03bf\u03c2 \u03b2\u03b1\u03c1\u03b9\u03ac \u03c4\u03c1\u03b1\u03c5\u03bc\u03b1\u03c4\u03b9\u03c3\u03bc\u03ad\u03bd\u03bf\u03c2. \u039f\u03b9 \u03c0\u03c5\u03c1\u03bf\u03b2\u03bf\u03bb\u03b9\u03c3\u03bc\u03bf\u03af \u03ad\u03c0\u03b5\u03c6\u03c4\u03b1\u03bd \u03c3\u03c5\u03bd\u03ad\u03c7\u03b5\u03b9\u03b1 \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 \u03bf\u03b9 \u03c3\u03c6\u03b1\u03af\u03c1\u03b5\u03c2 \u03b5\u03af\u03c7\u03b1\u03bd \u03b3\u03b1\u03b6\u03ce\u03c3\u03b5\u03b9 \u03c4\u03bf \u03bc\u03b9\u03ba\u03c1\u03cc \u03b1\u03c5\u03c4\u03bf\u03ba\u03af\u03bd\u03b7\u03c4\u03bf \u03c0\u03bf\u03c5 \u03ba\u03ac\u03bb\u03c5\u03c0\u03c4\u03b5 \u03c4\u03bf\u03bd \u03c4\u03c1\u03b1\u03c5\u03bc\u03b1\u03c4\u03af\u03b1 ...}}</ref> His name was in the indictment against the junta members during the [[Greek Junta Trials]].<ref name=\"Rodak\u0113s1976\">{{cite book|author=Perikl\u0113s Rodak\u0113s|title=Hoi Dikes t\u0113s Chountas: Dik\u0113 Polytechneiou|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WN4cAAAAIAAJ|accessdate=6 July 2013|year=1976|publisher=Ekdoseis D\u0113mokratikoi Kairoi|page=2030|quote=...\u03ba\u03b1\u03af \u03c4\u03bf\u03cd\u03c2 \u03bc\u03ad \u03b1\u03cd\u03c4\u03ac \u03ac\u03bd\u03b1\u03bc\u03b5\u03bc\u03b9\u03b3\u03bc\u03ad\u03bd\u03bf\u03c5\u03c2 \u03c0\u03bf\u03bb\u03af\u03c4\u03b1\u03c2 \u03cc\u03c0\u03bb\u03bf\u03c6\u03bf\u03c1\u03bf\u03cd\u03bd\u03c4\u03b1\u03c2, \u03b5\u03c6\u03bf- \u03bd\u03b5\u03cd\u03b8\u03b7\u03c3\u03b1\u03bd \u03bf\u03af \u0392\u03b1\u03c3\u03af\u03bb\u03b5\u03b9\u03bf\u03c2 \u03a6\u03b1\u03bc\u03ad\u03bb\u03bf\u03c2, \u0395\u039d\u039f\u0395- \u03af\u0391\u039d\u03cb \u03a4\u039f\u039a\u0399\u03af\u03af \u03ba\u03b1\u03af \u0394\u03b9\u03bf\u03bc\u03ae\u03b4\u03b7\u03c2 \u039a\u03bf\u03bc\u03bd\u03b7\u03bd\u03cc\u03c2. \u039f\u03af \u03bc\u03ad\u03bd \u03b4\u03cd\u03bf \u03c0\u03c1\u03ce\u03c4\u03bf\u03b9 \u03c6\u03ad\u03c1\u03bf\u03bd\u03c4\u03b1\u03b9 \u03b4\u03b9\u03ac \u03c4\u03bf\u03cd \u03b2\u03bf\u03c5\u03bb\u03b5\u03cd\u03bc\u03b1\u03c4\u03bf\u03c2 \u03ce\u03c2 \u03c6\u03bf\u03bd\u03b5\u03c5\u03b8\u03ad\u03bd\u03c4\u03b5\u03c2 \u03cd\u03c0\u03cc \u03c4\u03bf\u03cd \u0389\u03bb. \u03a4\u03c3\u03b1\u03bc\u03c0\u03bf\u03cd\u03c1\u03b1 ...}}</ref>\n\n==Recognition==\nDiomidis Komninos is considered by many a heroic symbol of the [[Athens Polytechnic uprising]].<ref name=\"Athens News\">Albert Coerant, {{cite web |url=http://www.athensnews.gr/athweb/nathens.print_unique?e=C&f=12936&m=A08&aa=1&eidos=A |title=\"The boy who braved the tanks\" |accessdate=2008-01-18 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080118222959/http://www.athensnews.gr/athweb/nathens.print_unique?e=C&f=12936&m=A08&aa=1&eidos=A |archivedate=January 18, 2008 }}, ''Athens News'', 16 November 2001. Quote: ''This story is inspired by the heroic death of Diomedes Komninos, a worthy son of the Greek people. In November 1973 he went to the Polytechnic to fight for the freedom of his country. He would never come back. He was 16.''</ref><ref name=\"Lymperak\u01131976\">{{cite book|author=Margarita Lymperak\u0113|title=To myst\u0113rio|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0wsKAQAAIAAJ|accessdate=6 July 2013|year=1976|publisher=Kedros|page=123|quote=\u0395\u03b3\u03ce \u03c3\u03b5 \u03c6\u03c9\u03bd\u03ac\u03b6\u03c9, \u03c6\u03c9\u03bd\u03ac\u03b6\u03c9 \u0394\u03b9\u03bf\u03bc\u03ae\u03b4\u03b7\u03c2 \u039a\u03bf\u03bc\u03bd\u03b7\u03bd\u03cc\u03c2, \u03bc\u03bf\u03c5 \u03bb\u03b5\u03c2 \u03c0\u03b1\u03c1\u03ce\u03bd\u00bb. \u0391\u03c5\u03c4\u03ac \u03b5\u03af\u03c0\u03b5 \u03ad\u03bd\u03b1\u03c2 \u03b5\u03c1\u03b3\u03ac\u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u03c3\u03c4\u03bf\u03bd \u03c4\u03ac\u03c6\u03bf \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5 \u03bc\u03b1\u03b8\u03b7\u03c4\u03ae \u0394\u03b9\u03bf\u03bc\u03ae\u03b4\u03b7 \u03c0\u03bf\u03cd \u03b4\u03bf\u03bb\u03bf\u03c6\u03bf\u03bd\u03ae\u03b8\u03b7\u03ba\u03b5 \u03c3\u03c4\u03b9\u03c2 16 \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5 \u039d\u03bf\u03ad\u03bc\u03b2\u03c1\u03b7 \u03c4\u03b7 \u03c3\u03c4\u03b9\u03b3\u03bc\u03b7 \u03c0\u03bf\u03cd \u03c0\u03b7\u03b3\u03b5 \u03bd\u03b1 \u03c3\u03b7\u03ba\u03ce\u03c3\u03b5\u03b9 \u03b1\u03c5\u03c4\u03bf\u03cd\u03c2 \u03c0\u03bf\u03cd \u03b8\u03ad\u03c1\u03b9\u03b6\u03b5 \u03c4\u03bf \u03c0\u03bf\u03bb\u03c5\u03b2\u03cc\u03bb\u03bf \u03c3\u03c4\u03b7\u03bd \u03a0\u03b1\u03c4\u03b7\u03c3\u03af\u03c9\u03bd ...}}</ref><ref name=\"\u039d\u03c4\u03b1\u03bb\u03bf\u03c5\u03ba\u03b1\u03c22006\">{{cite book|author=\u039c\u03b1\u03bd\u03c9\u03bb\u03b7\u03c2 \u039d\u03c4\u03b1\u03bb\u03bf\u03c5\u03ba\u03b1\u03c2|title=\u0395\u03bb\u03bb\u03b7\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03bf \u03c1\u03bf\u03ba: \u03b9\u03c3\u03c4\u03bf\u03c1\u03b9\u03b1 \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u03bd\u03b5\u03b1\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03b7\u03c2 \u03ba\u03bf\u03c5\u03bb\u03c4\u03bf\u03c5\u03c1\u03b1\u03c2 \u03b1\u03c0\u03bf \u03c4\u03b7 \u03b3\u03b5\u03bd\u03b9\u03b1 \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5 \u03a7\u03b1\u03bf\u03c5\u03c2 \u03bc\u03b5\u03a7\u03c1\u03b9 \u03c4\u03bf\u03bd \u03b8\u03b1\u03bd\u03b1\u03c4\u03bf \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5 \u03a0\u03b1\u03c5\u03bb\u03bf\u03c5 \u03a3\u03b9\u03b4\u03b7\u03c1\u03bf\u03c0\u03bf\u03c5\u03bb\u03bf\u03c5|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JpWfAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=6 July 2013|year=2006|publisher=\u0391\u03b3\u03ba\u03c5\u03c1\u03b1|isbn=978-960-422-386-2|page=301|quote=\u0394\u03b5\u03be\u03b9\u03ac, \u03bf \u0394\u03b9\u03bf\u03bc\u03ae\u03b4\u03b7\u03c2 \u039a\u03bf\u03bc\u03bd\u03b7\u03bd\u03cc\u03c2, \u03ad\u03bd\u03b1\u03c2 \u03b1\u03c0\u03cc \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5\u03c2 \u03bc\u03b1\u03b8\u03b7\u03c4\u03ad\u03c2 \u03c0\u03bf\u03c5 \u03b5\u03bd\u03ce\u03b8\u03b7\u03ba\u03b1\u03bd \u03bc\u03b5 \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5\u03c2 \u03c6\u03bf\u03b9\u03c4\u03b7\u03c4\u03ad\u03c2. \u0388\u03c0\u03b5\u03c3\u03b5 \u03bd\u03b5\u03ba\u03c1\u03cc\u03c2 \u03bb\u03af\u03b3\u03b5\u03c2 \u03ce\u03c1\u03b5\u03c2 \u03c0\u03c1\u03b9\u03bd \u03b1\u03c0\u03cc \u03c4\u03b7\u03bd \u03b5\u03b9\u03c3\u03b2\u03bf\u03bb\u03ae, \u03b1\u03c0\u03cc \u03c3\u03c6\u03b1\u03af\u03c1\u03b1 \u03b1\u03c3\u03c4\u03c5\u03bd\u03bf\u03bc\u03b9\u03ba\u03bf\u03cd. \u0388\u03bc\u03b5\u03b9\u03bd\u03b5 \u03ba\u03b9 \u03b1\u03c5\u03c4\u03cc\u03c2 \u03c3\u03c4\u03b7\u03bd \u03ac\u03c3\u03c6\u03b1\u03bb\u03c4\u03bf \u03bc\u03b5 \u03c0\u03b1\u03b3\u03c9\u03bc\u03ad\u03bd\u03bf \u03c7\u03b1\u03bc\u03cc\u03b3\u03b5\u03bb\u03bf \u03bd\u03b1 \u03c6\u03c9\u03bd\u03ac\u03b6\u03b5\u03b9 \u03bc\u03ad\u03c7\u03c1\u03b9 \u03c4\u03bf\u03bd \u03ac\u03bb\u03bb\u03bf ...}}</ref> The student uprising is credited with helping trigger the eventual collapse of the military regime which ruled Greece since April 21, 1967. Nevertheless, the Polytechnic uprising was used as a pretext by junta hardliner Brigadier [[Dimitrios Ioannides]] to overthrow [[Georgios Papadopoulos|George Papadopoulos]] on November 25, 1973 and to put an end to a \"liberalisation process\" headed by [[Spiros Markezinis]]. The Ioannidis regime collapsed on July 1974 following the [[1974 Cypriot coup d'\u00e9tat|escalation of events]] in [[Cyprus]] that led to the ''[[Metapolitefsi]]''.\n\nPoet Anestis Evengelou has created a collection of [[Apostrophe (figure of speech)|apostrophic]] poems, resembling hymns or prayers, titled after Komnenos in which he mentions: \"Seventeen years old. Volunteer carrier of the casualties. Razed by bullets the Night of the Great Slaughter. 17 November '73 at the Polytechnic\".<ref name=\"Mark\u00f3poulos2006\">{{cite book|author=Than\u00e1s\u012bs E. Mark\u00f3poulos|title=\u0391\u03bd\u03ad\u03c3\u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u0395\u03c5\u03b1\u03b3\u03b3\u03ad\u03bb\u03bf\u03c5: \u03bf \u03c0\u03bf\u03b9\u03b7\u03c4\u03ae\u03c2, \u03bf \u03c0\u03b5\u03b6\u03bf\u03b3\u03c1\u03ac\u03c6\u03bf\u03c2, \u03bf \u03ba\u03c1\u03b9\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc\u03c2|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=d41iAAAAMAAJ&q=%22%CE%94%CE%B9%CE%BF%CE%BC%CE%AE%CE%B4%CE%B7%CF%82+%CE%9A%CE%BF%CE%BC%CE%BD%CE%B7%CE%BD%CF%8C%CF%82%22&dq=%22%CE%94%CE%B9%CE%BF%CE%BC%CE%AE%CE%B4%CE%B7%CF%82+%CE%9A%CE%BF%CE%BC%CE%BD%CE%B7%CE%BD%CF%8C%CF%82%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=qYHZUberJ8bjrQGLxIHYCQ&ved=0CDQQ6AEwAQ|accessdate=7 July 2013|year=2006|publisher=\u03a0\u03b1\u03bd. \u0393. \u03a3\u03bf\u03ba\u03cc\u03bb\u03b7\u03c2|isbn=978-960-8264-78-6|page=254|quote=\u03a4\u03b5\u03bb\u03bf\u03c2 \u03b4\u03b5\u03bd \u03b5\u03b9\u03bd\u03b1\u03b9 \u03c7\u03c9\u03c1\u03b9\u03c2 \u03b5\u03bd\u03b4\u03b9\u03b1\u03c6\u03b5\u03c1\u03bf\u03bd \u03bc\u03b9\u03b1 \u03ba\u03bf\u03bd\u03c4\u03b9\u03bd\u03bf\u03c4\u03b5\u03c1\u03b7 \u03c0\u03c1\u03bf\u03c3\u03b5\u03b3\u03b3\u03b9\u03c3\u03b7 \u03c3\u03b5 \u03bc\u03b9\u03b1 \u03bc\u03bf\u03c1\u03c6\u03b7 \u03b1\u03c0\u03bf\u03c3\u03c4\u03c1\u03bf\u03c6\u03b9\u03ba\u03bf\u03c5 \u03c0\u03bf\u03b9\u03b7\u03bc\u03b1\u03c4\u03bf\u03c2, \u03c0\u03bf\u03c5 \u03b5\u03be\u03b1\u03b9\u03c1\u03b5\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03b1 \u03b8\u03c5\u03bc\u03b9\u03b6\u03bf\u03c5\u03bd \u03c5\u03bc\u03bd\u03bf, \u03c9\u03b4\u03b7, \u03b1\u03bb\u03bb\u03b1 \u03c3\u03c5\u03bd\u03b7\u03b8\u03b5\u03c3\u03c4\u03b5\u03c1\u03b1 \u03b5\u03c7\u03bf\u03c5\u03bd \u03c4\u03bf \u03c3\u03c7\u03b7\u03bc\u03b1 \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u03c0\u03c1\u03bf\u03c3\u03b5\u03c5\u03c7\u03b7\u03c2. \u03a3\u03c4\u03b7\u03bd \u03c0\u03c1\u03c9\u03c4\u03b7 \u03c0\u03b5\u03c1\u03b9\u03c0\u03c4\u03c9\u03c3\u03b7 \u03b1\u03bd\u03b7\u03ba\u03bf\u03c5\u03bd \u03c4\u03b1 \u03c0\u03bf\u03b9\u03b7\u03bc\u03b1\u03c4\u03b1 \"\u0394\u03b9\u03bf\u03bc\u03b7\u03b4\u03b7\u03c2 \u039a\u03bf\u03bc\u03bd\u03b7\u03bd\u03bf\u03c2\"}}</ref><ref name=\"Euangelou2007\">{{cite book|author=Anest\u0113s Euangelou|title=Ta poi\u0113mata: (1956-1993)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NIBiAAAAMAAJ&q=%CE%B4%CE%B9%CE%BF%CE%BC%CE%AE%CE%B4%CE%B7%CF%82+%CE%BA%CE%BF%CE%BC%CE%BD%CE%B7%CE%BD%CF%8C%CF%82&dq=%CE%B4%CE%B9%CE%BF%CE%BC%CE%AE%CE%B4%CE%B7%CF%82+%CE%BA%CE%BF%CE%BC%CE%BD%CE%B7%CE%BD%CF%8C%CF%82&hl=en&sa=X&ei=cY7ZUdDTBMeoqgGf-ICQCw&ved=0CE4Q6AEwBQ|accessdate=7 July 2013|year=2007|publisher=Ekdoseis Kapani|page=203|quote=\u0394\u03b5\u03ba\u03b1\u03b5\u03c6\u03c4\u03ac \u03c7\u03c1\u03bf\u03bd\u03ce\u03bd. \u0395\u03b8\u03b5\u03bb\u03bf\u03bd\u03c4\u03ae\u03c2 \u03c4\u03c1\u03b1\u03c5\u03bc\u03b1\u03c4\u03b9\u03bf\u03c6\u03bf\u03c1\u03ad\u03b1\u03c2. \u0393\u03b1\u03b6\u03ce\u03b8\u03b7\u03ba\u03b5 \u03b1\u03c0\u03cc \u03c3\u03c6\u03b1\u03af\u03c1\u03b5\u03c2 \u03c4\u03b7 \u039d\u03cd\u03c7\u03c4\u03b1 \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u039c\u03b5\u03b3\u03ac\u03bb\u03b7\u03c2 \u03a3\u03c6\u03b1\u03b3\u03ae\u03c2. 17 \u039d\u03bf\u03ad\u03bc\u03b2\u03c1\u03b7 '73 \u03c3\u03c4\u03bf \u03a0\u03bf\u03bb\u03c5\u03c4\u03b5\u03c7\u03bd\u03b5\u03af\u03bf.}}</ref>\n\nPoet Dimitris Ravanis-Rentis wrote the poetic dedication \"To Diomidis Komninos\".<ref name=Imathia>{{cite web|title=\u0392\u03c1\u03b5\u03b9\u03c4\u03b5 \u03c5\u03bb\u03b9\u03ba\u03bf \u03b3\u03b9\u03b1 \u03c4\u03b7 \u03b3\u03b9\u03bf\u03c1\u03c4\u03b7 \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5 \u03c0\u03bf\u03bb\u03c5\u03c4\u03b5\u03c7\u03bd\u03b5\u03b9\u03bf\u03c5|url=http://ima-edu.webnode.gr/products/\u03b2\u03c1\u03b5\u03b9\u03c4\u03b5-\u03c5\u03bb\u03b9\u03ba\u03bf-\u03b3\u03b9\u03b1-\u03c4\u03b7-\u03b3\u03b9\u03bf\u03c1\u03c4\u03b7-\u03c4\u03bf\u03c5-\u03c0\u03bf\u03bb\u03c5\u03c4\u03b5\u03c7\u03bd\u03b5\u03b9\u03bf\u03c5/|publisher=Imathia Educational portal}}</ref> \n \nHis torn shirt is exhibited at the memorial of the victims of the Polytechnic uprising and was held by [[Hortensia Allende]] to wipe her tears, during her visit there.<ref name=\"Society1976\">{{cite book|author=Hellenic American Society|title=Journal of the Hellenic diaspora|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GkUeAQAAMAAJ&q=Diomedes+Komnenos&dq=Diomedes+Komnenos&hl=en&sa=X&ei=FP2-T6WtJMT66QHXsaDVCg&redir_esc=y|accessdate=24 May 2012|year=1976|publisher=Pella Pub. Co.|page=32}}</ref>\n\n== Citations and notes ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Komninos, Diomidis}}\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:1973 deaths]]\n[[Category:Deaths by firearm in Greece]]\n[[Category:Resistance to the Greek junta]]\n[[Category:Greek murder victims]]\n[[Category:Student protests in Greece]]\n[[Category:People murdered in Greece]]\n[[Category:1973 murders in Europe]]\n[[Category:1970s murders in Greece]]\n[[Category:1973 crimes in Greece]]\n", "text_old": "[[Image:Diomedes Komnenos.jpg|150px|thumb|Diomidis Komninos]]\n'''Diomidis Komninos''' ({{lang-el|\u0394\u03b9\u03bf\u03bc\u03ae\u03b4\u03b7\u03c2 \u039a\u03bf\u03bc\u03bd\u03b7\u03bd\u03cc\u03c2}}; 1956\u20131973), a [[Cyprus|Cypriot]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mixanitouxronou.com.cy/stiles/sinevi-simera/to-agori-pou-nikise-ta-tanks-o-kyprios-diomidis-komninos-itan-o-protos-nekros-tou-polytechniou-dolofonithike-en-psychro-apo-ena-frouro-me-mia-sfera-stin-kardia/ |title=\u00ab\u03a4\u03bf \u03b1\u03b3\u03cc\u03c1\u03b9 \u03c0\u03bf\u03c5 \u03bd\u03af\u03ba\u03b7\u03c3\u03b5 \u03c4\u03b1 \u03c4\u03b1\u03bd\u03ba\u03c2\u00bb. \u039f \u039a\u03cd\u03c0\u03c1\u03b9\u03bf\u03c2 \u0394\u03b9\u03bf\u03bc\u03ae\u03b4\u03b7\u03c2 \u039a\u03bf\u03bc\u03bd\u03b7\u03bd\u03cc\u03c2 \u03ae\u03c4\u03b1\u03bd \u03bf \u03c0\u03c1\u03ce\u03c4\u03bf\u03c2 \u03bd\u03b5\u03ba\u03c1\u03cc\u03c2 \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5 \u03a0\u03bf\u03bb\u03c5\u03c4\u03b5\u03c7\u03bd\u03b5\u03af\u03bf\u03c5. \u0394\u03bf\u03bb\u03bf\u03c6\u03bf\u03bd\u03ae\u03b8\u03b7\u03ba\u03b5 \u03b5\u03bd \u03c8\u03c5\u03c7\u03c1\u03ce \u03b1\u03c0\u03cc \u03ad\u03bd\u03b1 \u03c6\u03c1\u03bf\u03c5\u03c1\u03cc \u03bc\u03b5 \u03bc\u03b9\u03b1 \u03c3\u03c6\u03b1\u03af\u03c1\u03b1 \u03c3\u03c4\u03b7\u03bd \u03ba\u03b1\u03c1\u03b4\u03b9\u03ac |website=\u039c\u03b7\u03c7\u03b1\u03bd\u03ae \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5 \u03a7\u03c1\u03cc\u03bd\u03bf\u03c5 | access-date=April 22, 2018| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180422170915/http://www.mixanitouxronou.com.cy/stiles/sinevi-simera/to-agori-pou-nikise-ta-tanks-o-kyprios-diomidis-komninos-itan-o-protos-nekros-tou-polytechniou-dolofonithike-en-psychro-apo-ena-frouro-me-mia-sfera-stin-kardia/ |archivedate=April 22, 2018 }}</ref> [[Greece|Greek]] high school student, was the first casualty of the [[Athens Polytechnic uprising]].<ref name=\"Chatz\u0113s\u014dkrat\u0113s2004\"/><ref name=\"Zaous\u0113s1998\">{{cite book|author=Alexandros L. Zaous\u0113s|title=Ho empaigmos: 21 Apriliou 1967-24 Iouliou 1974|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=N0toAAAAMAAJ&q=%CE%94%CE%B9%CE%BF%CE%BC%CE%AE%CE%B4%CE%B7%CF%82+%CE%9A%CE%BF%CE%BC%CE%BD%CE%B7%CE%BD%CF%8C%CF%82&dq=%CE%94%CE%B9%CE%BF%CE%BC%CE%AE%CE%B4%CE%B7%CF%82+%CE%9A%CE%BF%CE%BC%CE%BD%CE%B7%CE%BD%CF%8C%CF%82&hl=en&sa=X&ei=bjzYUaeELoKlrAGa7IHIDA&ved=0CFsQ6AEwBw|accessdate=6 July 2013|year=1998|publisher=Ekdoseis Papaz\u0113s\u0113|page=229|quote=\u0395\u03c0\u03af\u03c3\u03b7\u03c2 \u03ad\u03c7\u03b5\u03b9 \u03c5\u03c0\u03bf\u03c3\u03c4\u03b7\u03c1\u03b9\u03c7\u03b8\u03b5\u03af \u03cc\u03c4\u03b9 \u03bf\u03c5\u03c3\u03b9\u03b1\u03c3\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03ac \u03bf \u03bc\u03cc\u03bd\u03bf\u03c2 \u03bd\u03b5\u03ba\u03c1\u03cc\u03c2 \u03bc\u03c0\u03c1\u03bf\u03c3\u03c4\u03ac \u03c3\u03c4\u03bf \u03a0\u03bf\u03bb\u03c5\u03c4\u03b5\u03c7\u03bd\u03b5\u03af\u03bf \u03ae\u03c4\u03b1\u03bd \u03bf \u03ac\u03c4\u03c5\u03c7\u03bf\u03c2 \u03ad\u03c6\u03b7\u03b2\u03bf\u03c2 \u03bc\u03b1\u03b8\u03b7\u03c4\u03ae\u03c2, \u03bf \u0394\u03b9\u03bf\u03bc\u03ae\u03b4\u03b7\u03c2 \u039a\u03bf\u03bc\u03bd\u03b7\u03bd\u03cc\u03c2.}}</ref> He was shot opposite the main gate of the Polytechnic.<ref name=\"Chatz\u0113s\u014dkrat\u0113s2004\">{{cite book|author=D\u0113m\u0113tr\u0113s Chatz\u0113s\u014dkrat\u0113s|title=\u03a0\u03bf\u03bb\u03c5\u03c4\u03b5\u03a7\u03bd\u03b5\u03b9\u03bf '73: \u0391\u03bd\u03b1\u03c3\u03c4\u03bf\u03a7\u03b1\u03c3\u03bc\u03bf\u03c2 \u03bc\u03b9\u03b1\u03c2 \u03c0\u03c1\u03b1\u03b3\u03bc\u03b1\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03bf\u03c4\u03b7\u03c4\u03b1\u03c2|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Z5cOAQAAMAAJ&q=%CE%94%CE%B9%CE%BF%CE%BC%CE%AE%CE%B4%CE%B7%CF%82+%CE%9A%CE%BF%CE%BC%CE%BD%CE%B7%CE%BD%CF%8C%CF%82&dq=%CE%94%CE%B9%CE%BF%CE%BC%CE%AE%CE%B4%CE%B7%CF%82+%CE%9A%CE%BF%CE%BC%CE%BD%CE%B7%CE%BD%CF%8C%CF%82&hl=en&sa=X&ei=bjzYUaeELoKlrAGa7IHIDA&ved=0CEgQ6AEwBA|accessdate=6 July 2013|year=2004|publisher=\u03a0\u03bf\u03bb\u03b9\u03c2|isbn=978-960-435-013-1|page=142|quote=10:15 \u03bc.\u03bc. \u039f \u03c0\u03c1\u03ce\u03c4\u03bf\u03c2 \u03bd\u03b5\u03ba\u03c1\u03cc\u03c2 \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5 \u03a0\u03bf\u03bb\u03c5\u03c4\u03b5\u03c7\u03bd\u03b5\u03af\u03bf\u03c5. \u039f \u03b4\u03b5\u03ba\u03b1\u03b5\u03c6\u03c4\u03ac\u03c7\u03c1\u03bf\u03bd\u03bf\u03c2 \u03bc\u03b1\u03b8\u03b7\u03c4\u03ae\u03c2 \u0394\u03b9\u03bf\u03bc\u03ae\u03b4\u03b7\u03c2 \u039a\u03bf\u03bc\u03bd\u03b7\u03bd\u03cc\u03c2 \u03c0\u03c5\u03c1\u03bf\u03b2\u03bf\u03bb\u03b5\u03af\u03c4\u03b1\u03b9 \u03b8\u03b1\u03bd\u03ac\u03c3\u03b9\u03bc\u03b1 \u03c3\u03c4\u03b7\u03bd \u03a0\u03b1\u03c4\u03b7\u03c3\u03af\u03c9\u03bd \u03b1\u03c0\u03ad\u03bd\u03b1\u03bd\u03c4\u03b9 \u03b1\u03c0\u03cc \u03c4\u03b7\u03bd \u03ba\u03b5\u03bd\u03c4\u03c1\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae \u03c0\u03cd\u03bb\u03b7.}}</ref>\n\n==The events==\nOn the night of Friday, November 16, 1973, police forces started confronting the thousands of protesters gathered inside and outside the Polytechnic campus, located on [[Patission Street]], one of the busiest in Athens. Komnenos was one of the many high school students barricaded inside the Polytechnic. At about 10:00 pm, the police used guns and smoke-bombs to evacuate the streets from the protesters. At the time, Komninos had joined other students on the corner of [[Tritis Septemvriou Street]] and Averof St.,<ref>Intersection coordinates: ({{coord|37|59|20|N|23|43|45|E|}})</ref> exactly across from the Polytechnic. It is reported that Komninos went from the student side to the middle of the street toward the police lines and raising his hands he told them from a distance of about forty metres: \"If you are men come and hit us from up close\".<ref name=\"Pliatsika-Pansel\u0113nou1976\">{{cite book|author=Eph\u0113 Pliatsika-Pansel\u0113nou|title=Katachtemene chora : mythistorema|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JQIKAQAAIAAJ&q=%22%CE%94%CE%B9%CE%BF%CE%BC%CE%AE%CE%B4%CE%B7%CF%82+%CE%9A%CE%BF%CE%BC%CE%BD%CE%B7%CE%BD%CF%8C%CF%82%22&dq=%22%CE%94%CE%B9%CE%BF%CE%BC%CE%AE%CE%B4%CE%B7%CF%82+%CE%9A%CE%BF%CE%BC%CE%BD%CE%B7%CE%BD%CF%8C%CF%82%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=W0fYUdgkyf6oAcrbgKgK&ved=0CC4Q6AEwAA|accessdate=6 July 2013|year=1976|publisher=Ekdoseis Synchrone epoche|pages=292\u2013294|quote=\u038c \u0394\u03b9\u03bf\u03bc\u03ae\u03b4\u03b7\u03c2 \u039a\u03bf\u03bc\u03bd\u03b7\u03bd\u03cc\u03c2, \u03b2\u03b3\u03ae\u03ba\u03b5 \u03be\u03b1\u03c6\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03ac \u03c3\u03c4\u03b7 \u03bc\u03ad\u03c3\u03b7 \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5 \u03b4\u03c1\u03cc\u03bc\u03bf\u03c5, \u03c3\u03ae\u03ba\u03c9\u03c3\u03b5 \u03c4\u03b1 \u03c7\u03ad\u03c1\u03b9\u03b1, \u03b2\u03bb\u03ad\u03c0\u03bf\u03bd\u03c4\u03b1\u03c2 \u03c0\u03c1\u03bf\u03c2 \u03c4\u03b7 \u03bc\u03b5\u03c1\u03b9\u03ac \u03c4\u03c9\u03bd \u03b1\u03c3\u03c4\u03c5\u03bd\u03bf\u03bc\u03b9\u03ba\u03ce\u03bd, \u03c0\u03bf\u03c5 \u03b2\u03c1\u03af\u03c3\u03ba\u03bf\u03bd\u03c4\u03b1\u03bd \u03c3\u03b5 \u03b1\u03c0\u03cc\u03c3\u03c4\u03b1\u03c3\u03b7 \u03c3\u03b1\u03c1\u03ac\u03bd\u03c4\u03b1 \u03c0\u03b5\u03c1\u03af\u03c0\u03bf\u03c5 \u03bc\u03ad\u03c4\u03c1\u03c9\u03bd \u03ba\u03b1\u03af \u03b5\u03af\u03c0\u03b5: \"\"\u0391\u03bd \u03b5\u03af\u03c3\u03b1\u03c3\u03c4\u03b5 \u03ac\u03bd\u03c4\u03c1\u03b5\u03c2, \u03b5\u03bb\u03ac\u03c4\u03b5 \u03bd\u03b1 \u03bc\u03b1\u03c2 \u03c7\u03c4\u03c5\u03c0\u03ae\u03c3\u03b5\u03c4\u03b5 \u03b1\u03c0\u03cc \u03ba\u03bf\u03bd\u03c4\u03ac.}}</ref> The students were reportedly hit by sniper fire from the roofs of the neighbouring buildings. Komnenos was killed at 10:15&nbsp;p.m. when a bullet pierced his heart.<ref name=\"Chatz\u0113s\u014dkrat\u0113s2004\"/><ref name=\"Panourgi\u00e11995\">{{cite book|author=Eleni Neni K. Panourgi\u00e1|title=Fragments of Death, Fables of Identity: An Athenian Anthropography|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mKJcA4Cj03gC&pg=PA145|accessdate=24 May 2012|year=1995|publisher=Univ of Wisconsin Press|isbn=978-0-299-14564-4|page=145}}</ref><ref name=\"Gatos2002\">{{cite book|author=Gi\u014drgos Gatos|title=Polytechneio '73: reportaz me t\u0113n historia : to chroniko, hoi martyries, ta \u1e0fokoumenta|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tOs0AAAAMAAJ&q=%CE%94%CE%B9%CE%BF%CE%BC%CE%AE%CE%B4%CE%B7%CF%82+%CE%9A%CE%BF%CE%BC%CE%BD%CE%B7%CE%BD%CF%8C%CF%82&dq=%CE%94%CE%B9%CE%BF%CE%BC%CE%AE%CE%B4%CE%B7%CF%82+%CE%9A%CE%BF%CE%BC%CE%BD%CE%B7%CE%BD%CF%8C%CF%82&hl=en&sa=X&ei=bjzYUaeELoKlrAGa7IHIDA&ved=0CEIQ6AEwAw|accessdate=6 July 2013|year=2002|publisher=Ekdoseis Philippot\u0113|page=52|quote=\u03a4\u03cc\u03c4\u03b5 \u03b1\u03ba\u03bf\u03cd\u03c3\u03c4\u03b7\u03ba\u03b1\u03bd \u03c0\u03c5\u03c1\u03bf\u03b2\u03bf\u03bb\u03b9\u03c3\u03bc\u03bf\u03af \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 \u03bf \u03bd\u03b5\u03b1\u03c1\u03cc\u03c2 \u03c0\u03bf\u03c5 \u03ae\u03c4\u03b1\u03bd \u03bf \u03bc\u03b1\u03b8\u03b7\u03c4\u03ae\u03c2 \u0394\u03b9\u03bf\u03bc\u03ae\u03b4\u03b7\u03c2 \u039a\u03bf\u03bc\u03bd\u03b7\u03bd\u03cc\u03c2, \u03ad\u03c0\u03b5\u03c3\u03b5 \u03c3\u03c4\u03bf \u03ad\u03b4\u03b1\u03c6\u03bf\u03c2 \u03b2\u03b1\u03c1\u03b9\u03ac \u03c4\u03c1\u03b1\u03c5\u03bc\u03b1\u03c4\u03b9\u03c3\u03bc\u03ad\u03bd\u03bf\u03c2. \u039f\u03b9 \u03c0\u03c5\u03c1\u03bf\u03b2\u03bf\u03bb\u03b9\u03c3\u03bc\u03bf\u03af \u03ad\u03c0\u03b5\u03c6\u03c4\u03b1\u03bd \u03c3\u03c5\u03bd\u03ad\u03c7\u03b5\u03b9\u03b1 \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 \u03bf\u03b9 \u03c3\u03c6\u03b1\u03af\u03c1\u03b5\u03c2 \u03b5\u03af\u03c7\u03b1\u03bd \u03b3\u03b1\u03b6\u03ce\u03c3\u03b5\u03b9 \u03c4\u03bf \u03bc\u03b9\u03ba\u03c1\u03cc \u03b1\u03c5\u03c4\u03bf\u03ba\u03af\u03bd\u03b7\u03c4\u03bf \u03c0\u03bf\u03c5 \u03ba\u03ac\u03bb\u03c5\u03c0\u03c4\u03b5 \u03c4\u03bf\u03bd \u03c4\u03c1\u03b1\u03c5\u03bc\u03b1\u03c4\u03af\u03b1 ...}}</ref> His name was in the indictment against the junta members during the [[Greek Junta Trials]].<ref name=\"Rodak\u0113s1976\">{{cite book|author=Perikl\u0113s Rodak\u0113s|title=Hoi Dikes t\u0113s Chountas: Dik\u0113 Polytechneiou|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WN4cAAAAIAAJ|accessdate=6 July 2013|year=1976|publisher=Ekdoseis D\u0113mokratikoi Kairoi|page=2030|quote=...\u03ba\u03b1\u03af \u03c4\u03bf\u03cd\u03c2 \u03bc\u03ad \u03b1\u03cd\u03c4\u03ac \u03ac\u03bd\u03b1\u03bc\u03b5\u03bc\u03b9\u03b3\u03bc\u03ad\u03bd\u03bf\u03c5\u03c2 \u03c0\u03bf\u03bb\u03af\u03c4\u03b1\u03c2 \u03cc\u03c0\u03bb\u03bf\u03c6\u03bf\u03c1\u03bf\u03cd\u03bd\u03c4\u03b1\u03c2, \u03b5\u03c6\u03bf- \u03bd\u03b5\u03cd\u03b8\u03b7\u03c3\u03b1\u03bd \u03bf\u03af \u0392\u03b1\u03c3\u03af\u03bb\u03b5\u03b9\u03bf\u03c2 \u03a6\u03b1\u03bc\u03ad\u03bb\u03bf\u03c2, \u0395\u039d\u039f\u0395- \u03af\u0391\u039d\u03cb \u03a4\u039f\u039a\u0399\u03af\u03af \u03ba\u03b1\u03af \u0394\u03b9\u03bf\u03bc\u03ae\u03b4\u03b7\u03c2 \u039a\u03bf\u03bc\u03bd\u03b7\u03bd\u03cc\u03c2. \u039f\u03af \u03bc\u03ad\u03bd \u03b4\u03cd\u03bf \u03c0\u03c1\u03ce\u03c4\u03bf\u03b9 \u03c6\u03ad\u03c1\u03bf\u03bd\u03c4\u03b1\u03b9 \u03b4\u03b9\u03ac \u03c4\u03bf\u03cd \u03b2\u03bf\u03c5\u03bb\u03b5\u03cd\u03bc\u03b1\u03c4\u03bf\u03c2 \u03ce\u03c2 \u03c6\u03bf\u03bd\u03b5\u03c5\u03b8\u03ad\u03bd\u03c4\u03b5\u03c2 \u03cd\u03c0\u03cc \u03c4\u03bf\u03cd \u0389\u03bb. \u03a4\u03c3\u03b1\u03bc\u03c0\u03bf\u03cd\u03c1\u03b1 ...}}</ref>\n\n==Recognition==\nDiomidis Komninos is considered by many a heroic symbol of the [[Athens Polytechnic uprising]].<ref name=\"Athens News\">Albert Coerant, {{cite web |url=http://www.athensnews.gr/athweb/nathens.print_unique?e=C&f=12936&m=A08&aa=1&eidos=A |title=\"The boy who braved the tanks\" |accessdate=2008-01-18 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080118222959/http://www.athensnews.gr/athweb/nathens.print_unique?e=C&f=12936&m=A08&aa=1&eidos=A |archivedate=January 18, 2008 }}, ''Athens News'', 16 November 2001. Quote: ''This story is inspired by the heroic death of Diomedes Komninos, a worthy son of the Greek people. In November 1973 he went to the Polytechnic to fight for the freedom of his country. He would never come back. He was 16.''</ref><ref name=\"Lymperak\u01131976\">{{cite book|author=Margarita Lymperak\u0113|title=To myst\u0113rio|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0wsKAQAAIAAJ|accessdate=6 July 2013|year=1976|publisher=Kedros|page=123|quote=\u0395\u03b3\u03ce \u03c3\u03b5 \u03c6\u03c9\u03bd\u03ac\u03b6\u03c9, \u03c6\u03c9\u03bd\u03ac\u03b6\u03c9 \u0394\u03b9\u03bf\u03bc\u03ae\u03b4\u03b7\u03c2 \u039a\u03bf\u03bc\u03bd\u03b7\u03bd\u03cc\u03c2, \u03bc\u03bf\u03c5 \u03bb\u03b5\u03c2 \u03c0\u03b1\u03c1\u03ce\u03bd\u00bb. \u0391\u03c5\u03c4\u03ac \u03b5\u03af\u03c0\u03b5 \u03ad\u03bd\u03b1\u03c2 \u03b5\u03c1\u03b3\u03ac\u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u03c3\u03c4\u03bf\u03bd \u03c4\u03ac\u03c6\u03bf \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5 \u03bc\u03b1\u03b8\u03b7\u03c4\u03ae \u0394\u03b9\u03bf\u03bc\u03ae\u03b4\u03b7 \u03c0\u03bf\u03cd \u03b4\u03bf\u03bb\u03bf\u03c6\u03bf\u03bd\u03ae\u03b8\u03b7\u03ba\u03b5 \u03c3\u03c4\u03b9\u03c2 16 \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5 \u039d\u03bf\u03ad\u03bc\u03b2\u03c1\u03b7 \u03c4\u03b7 \u03c3\u03c4\u03b9\u03b3\u03bc\u03b7 \u03c0\u03bf\u03cd \u03c0\u03b7\u03b3\u03b5 \u03bd\u03b1 \u03c3\u03b7\u03ba\u03ce\u03c3\u03b5\u03b9 \u03b1\u03c5\u03c4\u03bf\u03cd\u03c2 \u03c0\u03bf\u03cd \u03b8\u03ad\u03c1\u03b9\u03b6\u03b5 \u03c4\u03bf \u03c0\u03bf\u03bb\u03c5\u03b2\u03cc\u03bb\u03bf \u03c3\u03c4\u03b7\u03bd \u03a0\u03b1\u03c4\u03b7\u03c3\u03af\u03c9\u03bd ...}}</ref><ref name=\"\u039d\u03c4\u03b1\u03bb\u03bf\u03c5\u03ba\u03b1\u03c22006\">{{cite book|author=\u039c\u03b1\u03bd\u03c9\u03bb\u03b7\u03c2 \u039d\u03c4\u03b1\u03bb\u03bf\u03c5\u03ba\u03b1\u03c2|title=\u0395\u03bb\u03bb\u03b7\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03bf \u03c1\u03bf\u03ba: \u03b9\u03c3\u03c4\u03bf\u03c1\u03b9\u03b1 \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u03bd\u03b5\u03b1\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03b7\u03c2 \u03ba\u03bf\u03c5\u03bb\u03c4\u03bf\u03c5\u03c1\u03b1\u03c2 \u03b1\u03c0\u03bf \u03c4\u03b7 \u03b3\u03b5\u03bd\u03b9\u03b1 \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5 \u03a7\u03b1\u03bf\u03c5\u03c2 \u03bc\u03b5\u03a7\u03c1\u03b9 \u03c4\u03bf\u03bd \u03b8\u03b1\u03bd\u03b1\u03c4\u03bf \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5 \u03a0\u03b1\u03c5\u03bb\u03bf\u03c5 \u03a3\u03b9\u03b4\u03b7\u03c1\u03bf\u03c0\u03bf\u03c5\u03bb\u03bf\u03c5|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JpWfAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=6 July 2013|year=2006|publisher=\u0391\u03b3\u03ba\u03c5\u03c1\u03b1|isbn=978-960-422-386-2|page=301|quote=\u0394\u03b5\u03be\u03b9\u03ac, \u03bf \u0394\u03b9\u03bf\u03bc\u03ae\u03b4\u03b7\u03c2 \u039a\u03bf\u03bc\u03bd\u03b7\u03bd\u03cc\u03c2, \u03ad\u03bd\u03b1\u03c2 \u03b1\u03c0\u03cc \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5\u03c2 \u03bc\u03b1\u03b8\u03b7\u03c4\u03ad\u03c2 \u03c0\u03bf\u03c5 \u03b5\u03bd\u03ce\u03b8\u03b7\u03ba\u03b1\u03bd \u03bc\u03b5 \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5\u03c2 \u03c6\u03bf\u03b9\u03c4\u03b7\u03c4\u03ad\u03c2. \u0388\u03c0\u03b5\u03c3\u03b5 \u03bd\u03b5\u03ba\u03c1\u03cc\u03c2 \u03bb\u03af\u03b3\u03b5\u03c2 \u03ce\u03c1\u03b5\u03c2 \u03c0\u03c1\u03b9\u03bd \u03b1\u03c0\u03cc \u03c4\u03b7\u03bd \u03b5\u03b9\u03c3\u03b2\u03bf\u03bb\u03ae, \u03b1\u03c0\u03cc \u03c3\u03c6\u03b1\u03af\u03c1\u03b1 \u03b1\u03c3\u03c4\u03c5\u03bd\u03bf\u03bc\u03b9\u03ba\u03bf\u03cd. \u0388\u03bc\u03b5\u03b9\u03bd\u03b5 \u03ba\u03b9 \u03b1\u03c5\u03c4\u03cc\u03c2 \u03c3\u03c4\u03b7\u03bd \u03ac\u03c3\u03c6\u03b1\u03bb\u03c4\u03bf \u03bc\u03b5 \u03c0\u03b1\u03b3\u03c9\u03bc\u03ad\u03bd\u03bf \u03c7\u03b1\u03bc\u03cc\u03b3\u03b5\u03bb\u03bf \u03bd\u03b1 \u03c6\u03c9\u03bd\u03ac\u03b6\u03b5\u03b9 \u03bc\u03ad\u03c7\u03c1\u03b9 \u03c4\u03bf\u03bd \u03ac\u03bb\u03bb\u03bf ...}}</ref> The student uprising is credited with helping trigger the eventual collapse of the military regime which ruled Greece since April 21, 1967. Nevertheless, the Polytechnic uprising was used as a pretext by junta hardliner Brigadier [[Dimitrios Ioannides]] to overthrow [[Georgios Papadopoulos|George Papadopoulos]] on November 25, 1973 and to put an end to a \"liberalisation process\" headed by [[Spiros Markezinis]]. The Ioannidis regime collapsed on July 1974 following the [[1974 Cypriot coup d'\u00e9tat|escalation of events]] in [[Cyprus]] that led to the ''[[Metapolitefsi]]''.\n\nPoet Anestis Evengelou has created a collection of [[Apostrophe (figure of speech)|apostrophic]] poems, resembling hymns or prayers, titled after Komnenos in which he mentions: \"Seventeen years old. Volunteer carrier of the casualties. Razed by bullets the Night of the Great Slaughter. 17 November '73 at the Polytechnic\".<ref name=\"Mark\u00f3poulos2006\">{{cite book|author=Than\u00e1s\u012bs E. Mark\u00f3poulos|title=\u0391\u03bd\u03ad\u03c3\u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u0395\u03c5\u03b1\u03b3\u03b3\u03ad\u03bb\u03bf\u03c5: \u03bf \u03c0\u03bf\u03b9\u03b7\u03c4\u03ae\u03c2, \u03bf \u03c0\u03b5\u03b6\u03bf\u03b3\u03c1\u03ac\u03c6\u03bf\u03c2, \u03bf \u03ba\u03c1\u03b9\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc\u03c2|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=d41iAAAAMAAJ&q=%22%CE%94%CE%B9%CE%BF%CE%BC%CE%AE%CE%B4%CE%B7%CF%82+%CE%9A%CE%BF%CE%BC%CE%BD%CE%B7%CE%BD%CF%8C%CF%82%22&dq=%22%CE%94%CE%B9%CE%BF%CE%BC%CE%AE%CE%B4%CE%B7%CF%82+%CE%9A%CE%BF%CE%BC%CE%BD%CE%B7%CE%BD%CF%8C%CF%82%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=qYHZUberJ8bjrQGLxIHYCQ&ved=0CDQQ6AEwAQ|accessdate=7 July 2013|year=2006|publisher=\u03a0\u03b1\u03bd. \u0393. \u03a3\u03bf\u03ba\u03cc\u03bb\u03b7\u03c2|isbn=978-960-8264-78-6|page=254|quote=\u03a4\u03b5\u03bb\u03bf\u03c2 \u03b4\u03b5\u03bd \u03b5\u03b9\u03bd\u03b1\u03b9 \u03c7\u03c9\u03c1\u03b9\u03c2 \u03b5\u03bd\u03b4\u03b9\u03b1\u03c6\u03b5\u03c1\u03bf\u03bd \u03bc\u03b9\u03b1 \u03ba\u03bf\u03bd\u03c4\u03b9\u03bd\u03bf\u03c4\u03b5\u03c1\u03b7 \u03c0\u03c1\u03bf\u03c3\u03b5\u03b3\u03b3\u03b9\u03c3\u03b7 \u03c3\u03b5 \u03bc\u03b9\u03b1 \u03bc\u03bf\u03c1\u03c6\u03b7 \u03b1\u03c0\u03bf\u03c3\u03c4\u03c1\u03bf\u03c6\u03b9\u03ba\u03bf\u03c5 \u03c0\u03bf\u03b9\u03b7\u03bc\u03b1\u03c4\u03bf\u03c2, \u03c0\u03bf\u03c5 \u03b5\u03be\u03b1\u03b9\u03c1\u03b5\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03b1 \u03b8\u03c5\u03bc\u03b9\u03b6\u03bf\u03c5\u03bd \u03c5\u03bc\u03bd\u03bf, \u03c9\u03b4\u03b7, \u03b1\u03bb\u03bb\u03b1 \u03c3\u03c5\u03bd\u03b7\u03b8\u03b5\u03c3\u03c4\u03b5\u03c1\u03b1 \u03b5\u03c7\u03bf\u03c5\u03bd \u03c4\u03bf \u03c3\u03c7\u03b7\u03bc\u03b1 \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u03c0\u03c1\u03bf\u03c3\u03b5\u03c5\u03c7\u03b7\u03c2. \u03a3\u03c4\u03b7\u03bd \u03c0\u03c1\u03c9\u03c4\u03b7 \u03c0\u03b5\u03c1\u03b9\u03c0\u03c4\u03c9\u03c3\u03b7 \u03b1\u03bd\u03b7\u03ba\u03bf\u03c5\u03bd \u03c4\u03b1 \u03c0\u03bf\u03b9\u03b7\u03bc\u03b1\u03c4\u03b1 \"\u0394\u03b9\u03bf\u03bc\u03b7\u03b4\u03b7\u03c2 \u039a\u03bf\u03bc\u03bd\u03b7\u03bd\u03bf\u03c2\"}}</ref><ref name=\"Euangelou2007\">{{cite book|author=Anest\u0113s Euangelou|title=Ta poi\u0113mata: (1956-1993)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NIBiAAAAMAAJ&q=%CE%B4%CE%B9%CE%BF%CE%BC%CE%AE%CE%B4%CE%B7%CF%82+%CE%BA%CE%BF%CE%BC%CE%BD%CE%B7%CE%BD%CF%8C%CF%82&dq=%CE%B4%CE%B9%CE%BF%CE%BC%CE%AE%CE%B4%CE%B7%CF%82+%CE%BA%CE%BF%CE%BC%CE%BD%CE%B7%CE%BD%CF%8C%CF%82&hl=en&sa=X&ei=cY7ZUdDTBMeoqgGf-ICQCw&ved=0CE4Q6AEwBQ|accessdate=7 July 2013|year=2007|publisher=Ekdoseis Kapani|page=203|quote=\u0394\u03b5\u03ba\u03b1\u03b5\u03c6\u03c4\u03ac \u03c7\u03c1\u03bf\u03bd\u03ce\u03bd. \u0395\u03b8\u03b5\u03bb\u03bf\u03bd\u03c4\u03ae\u03c2 \u03c4\u03c1\u03b1\u03c5\u03bc\u03b1\u03c4\u03b9\u03bf\u03c6\u03bf\u03c1\u03ad\u03b1\u03c2. \u0393\u03b1\u03b6\u03ce\u03b8\u03b7\u03ba\u03b5 \u03b1\u03c0\u03cc \u03c3\u03c6\u03b1\u03af\u03c1\u03b5\u03c2 \u03c4\u03b7 \u039d\u03cd\u03c7\u03c4\u03b1 \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u039c\u03b5\u03b3\u03ac\u03bb\u03b7\u03c2 \u03a3\u03c6\u03b1\u03b3\u03ae\u03c2. 17 \u039d\u03bf\u03ad\u03bc\u03b2\u03c1\u03b7 '73 \u03c3\u03c4\u03bf \u03a0\u03bf\u03bb\u03c5\u03c4\u03b5\u03c7\u03bd\u03b5\u03af\u03bf.}}</ref>\n\nPoet Dimitris Ravanis-Rentis wrote the poetic dedication \"To Diomidis Komninos\".<ref name=Imathia>{{cite web|title=\u0392\u03c1\u03b5\u03b9\u03c4\u03b5 \u03c5\u03bb\u03b9\u03ba\u03bf \u03b3\u03b9\u03b1 \u03c4\u03b7 \u03b3\u03b9\u03bf\u03c1\u03c4\u03b7 \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5 \u03c0\u03bf\u03bb\u03c5\u03c4\u03b5\u03c7\u03bd\u03b5\u03b9\u03bf\u03c5|url=http://ima-edu.webnode.gr/products/\u03b2\u03c1\u03b5\u03b9\u03c4\u03b5-\u03c5\u03bb\u03b9\u03ba\u03bf-\u03b3\u03b9\u03b1-\u03c4\u03b7-\u03b3\u03b9\u03bf\u03c1\u03c4\u03b7-\u03c4\u03bf\u03c5-\u03c0\u03bf\u03bb\u03c5\u03c4\u03b5\u03c7\u03bd\u03b5\u03b9\u03bf\u03c5/|publisher=Imathia Educational portal}}</ref> \n \nHis torn shirt is exhibited at the memorial of the victims of the Polytechnic uprising and was held by [[Hortensia Allende]] to wipe her tears, during her visit there.<ref name=\"Society1976\">{{cite book|author=Hellenic American Society|title=Journal of the Hellenic diaspora|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GkUeAQAAMAAJ&q=Diomedes+Komnenos&dq=Diomedes+Komnenos&hl=en&sa=X&ei=FP2-T6WtJMT66QHXsaDVCg&redir_esc=y|accessdate=24 May 2012|year=1976|publisher=Pella Pub. Co.|page=32}}</ref>\n\n== Citations and notes ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Komninos, Diomidis}}\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:1973 deaths]]\n[[Category:Deaths by firearm in Greece]]\n[[Category:Resistance to the Greek military junta of 1967\u20131974]]\n[[Category:Greek murder victims]]\n[[Category:Student protests in Greece]]\n[[Category:People murdered in Greece]]\n[[Category:1973 murders in Europe]]\n[[Category:1970s murders in Greece]]\n[[Category:1973 crimes in Greece]]\n", "name_user": "Ceyockey", "label": "safe", "comment": "updating category (viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diomidis_Komninos"}
{"title_page": "Thomas Jefferson Bowen", "text_new": "'''Thomas Jefferson Bowen (1814 - 1875)'''  was an American expatriate Baptist missionary who spent considerable time of his missionary activities in [[Ijaiye|Ijaye]], [[Ogbomosho]] and a few other towns within the present [[Oyo State]]. His work established the foundation of the [[Nigerian Baptist Convention|Baptist mission]] in Nigeria.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=Baptist churches in Nigeria, 1850-1950 : accounts of their foundation and growth|last=Atanda|first=J.A.|date=1988|publisher=University Press|others=|isbn=978-9781549847|location=Ibadan|pages=xv-4|oclc=19106556}}</ref> Bowen's intention to proselytize to Africans in the interior in particular the [[Fula people|Fulanis]] was stopped by the [[Ilorin Emirate|Emir of Ilorin]], Bowen then concentrated his effort in [[Yorubaland]] until his return to America.\n\nWhile in U.S., he began to promote the creation of an America colony of free blacks in Africa.\n\n== Life ==\nBowen was born in [[Jackson County, Georgia|Jackson County]], Georgia.<ref name=\":0\" /> As a twenty two year old, he had experience in the quelling of a Native American uprising in Georgia and participated  in the second [[Second Seminole War|Seminole War]] .<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Meyer|first=Iysle E.|date=1982|title=T. J. Bowen and Central Africa: A Nineteenth-Century Missionary Delusion|journal=The International Journal of African Historical Studies|volume=15|issue=2|pages=247\u2013260|doi=10.2307/218549|jstor=218549}}</ref> Thereafter, he volunteered to join Texas in their independence fight against Mexico. It was during his stay in Texas that Bowen found Christ, upon his return to Georgia, he began to preaching and was soon ordained a minister.<ref name=\":1\" /> Bowen's church was affiliated with the American Baptist Mission but after a split in 1845, his allegiance shifted to the [[Southern Baptist Convention]] (SBC).  In 1848, when Bowen began to map out his vision of missionary activities in the interior of West Africa, the SBC was already involved in missionary work in China, India and in Liberia but the existing mission in Liberia was not promising, the [[Triennial Convention|Triennial Convention']]<nowiki/>s missionary effort on the West African coast sent fifteen white missionaries but nine died and the remainder returned to Boston.<ref name=\":0\" /> Bowen canvassed for a mission in the African interior of Central Africa or Western Sudan which constitutes present day Northern West Africa as a region more receptive to foreign missionaries.<ref name=\":0\" /> He had basic but limited knowledge of West Africa mostly from information he read about the activities of European explorers obtained from reference works from [[Penny Cyclopaedia|Penny cyclopaedia]] and Chamber's miscellany. Bowen also befriended W.B. Hodgson, a fellow Georgia native who had written works about the Berbers and Fulani's of Northern and Western Africa. [[Igboho]] was planned to be the starting point of his missionary work in Africa because it was close to the Fulani empire, converting the Fulani's was thought to be critical to spread Christianity in West Africa.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nUpon approval from the mission board of SBC, Bowen and two other colleagues Robert Hill and Hervey Goodale proceeded to Africa in December 1849,<ref name=\":0\" /> in  early 1850, the group reached the shores of Liberia en route to [[Badagry]] and further into Yorubaland. After arrival in Liberia, Bowen spent four months in Monrovia waiting for permission for movement to Badagry, during this time, Goodale died and Hill and Bowen went their separate ways. When he finally reached Badagry, Bowen was unable to go to Igboho due to [[Oyo Empire|civil war]] within Yorubaland. From Badagry he moved to [[Abeokuta]] and lived with European Methodist and Anglican missionaries such as [[Henry Townsend (missionary)|Henry Townsend]]. At Abeokuta, he bidded time studying [[Yoruba language]] and also giving military advice to the [[Egba people|Egba]] in their war with [[Dahomey]]. He also visited some Yoruba chiefs in present day [[Ibarapa people|Ibarapa]] and received a warm welcome at Ijaye were he established a station with the support of Aare Kurunmi.<ref name=\":1\" /> While in Yorubaland, Bowen's suffered from intermittent fever and his health deteriorated. He returned to America in 1852 to recuperate and to seek additional support for the mission. Bowen spent about a year in America, where he lobbied for support of the mission in Yorubaland and also got married. In 1853, he set sail for Ijaye with his new wife and two other missionary couples.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nAt Ijaye, Bowen and his wife built a chapel and established another outpost at Ogbomoso. However, Bowen's plan to move further north and convert the Fulani's was rebuffed by the ruling Emir of Ilorin who denied Bowen permission to preach in the city or to move further northwards with Ilorin's protection.<ref name=\":1\" /> in 1856, Bowen returned to America.\n\nIn 1857, Bowen published an account of his mission work, which also narrated his views on how the Christian world can transform Africa. The book received attention from American's interested in African affairs and from the [[American Colonization Society]], who were already familiar with Bowen, a frequent contributor to the society's journal, American repository.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:American missionaries]]\n[[Category:Christian missionaries in Nigeria]]\n", "text_old": "'''Thomas Jefferson Bowen (1814 - 1875)'''  was an American expatriate Baptist missionary who spent considerable time of his missionary activities in [[Ijaiye|Ijaye]], [[Ogbomosho]] and a few other towns within the present [[Oyo State]]. His work established the foundation of the [[Nigerian Baptist Convention|Baptist mission]] in Nigeria.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=Baptist churches in Nigeria, 1850-1950 : accounts of their foundation and growth|last=Atanda|first=J.A.|date=1988|publisher=University Press|others=|isbn=978-9781549847|location=Ibadan|pages=xv-4|oclc=19106556}}</ref> Bowen's intention to proselytize to Africans in the interior in particular the [[Fula people|Fulanis]] was stopped by the [[Ilorin Emirate|Emir of Ilorin]], Bowen then concentrated his effort in [[Yorubaland]] until his return to America.\n\nWhile in U.S., he began to promote the creation of an America colony of free blacks in Africa.\n\n== Life ==\nBowen was born in [[Jackson County, Georgia|Jackson County]], Georgia.<ref name=\":0\" /> As a twenty two year old, he had experience in the quelling of a Native American uprising in Georgia and participated  in the second [[Second Seminole War|Seminole War]] .<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Meyer|first=Iysle E.|date=1982|title=T. J. Bowen and Central Africa: A Nineteenth-Century Missionary Delusion|journal=The International Journal of African Historical Studies|volume=15|issue=2|pages=247\u2013260|doi=10.2307/218549|jstor=218549}}</ref> Thereafter, he volunteered to join Texas in their independence fight against Mexico. It was during his stay in Texas that Bowen found Christ, upon his return to Georgia, he began to preaching and was soon ordained a minister.<ref name=\":1\" /> Bowen's church was affiliated with the American Baptist Mission but after a split in 1845, his allegiance shifted to the [[Southern Baptist Convention]] (SBC).  In 1848, when Bowen began to map out his vision of missionary activities in the interior of West Africa, the SBC was already involved in missionary work in China, India and in Liberia but the existing mission in Liberia was not promising, the [[Triennial Convention|Triennial Convention']]<nowiki/>s missionary effort on the West African coast sent fifteen white missionaries but nine died and the remainder returned to Boston.<ref name=\":0\" /> Bowen canvassed for a mission in the African interior of Central Africa or Western Sudan which constitutes present day Northern West Africa as a region more receptive to foreign missionaries.<ref name=\":0\" /> He had basic but limited knowledge of West Africa mostly from information he read about the activities of European explorers obtained from reference works from [[Penny Cyclopaedia|Penny cyclopaedia]] and Chamber's miscellany. Bowen also befriended W.B. Hodgson, a fellow Georgia native who had written works about the Berbers and Fulani's of Northern and Western Africa. [[Igboho]] was planned to be the starting point of his missionary work in Africa because it was close to the Fulani empire, converting the Fulani's was thought to be critical to spread Christianity in West Africa.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nUpon approval from the mission board of SBC, Bowen and two other colleagues Robert Hill and Hervey Goodale proceeded to Africa in December 1849,<ref name=\":0\" /> in  early 1850, the group reached the shores of Liberia en route to [[Badagry]] and further into Yorubaland. After arrival in Liberia, Bowen spent four months in Monrovia waiting for permission for movement to Badagry, during this time, Goodale died and Hill and Bowen went their separate ways. When he finally reached Badagry, Bowen was unable to go to Igboho due to [[Oyo Empire|civil war]] within Yorubaland. From Badagry he moved to [[Abeokuta]] and lived with European Methodist and Anglican missionaries such as [[Henry Townsend (missionary)|Henry Townsend]]. At Abeokuta, he bidded time studying [[Yoruba language]] and also giving military advice to the [[Egba people|Egba]] in their war with [[Dahomey]]. He also visited some Yoruba chiefs in present day [[Ibarapa people|Ibarapa]] and received a warm welcome at Ijaye were he established a station with the support of Aare Kurunmi.<ref name=\":1\" /> While in Yorubaland, Bowen's suffered from intermittent fever and his health deteriorated. He returned to America in 1852 to recuperate and to seek additional support for the mission. Bowen spent about a year in America, where he lobbied for support of the mission in Yorubaland and also got married. In 1853, he set sail for Ijaye with his new wife and two other missionary couples.<ref name=\":0\" />  \n\nAt Ijaye, Bowen and his wife built a chapel and established another outpost at Ogbomoso. However, Bowen's plan to move further north and convert the Fulani's was rebuffed by the ruling Emir of Ilorin who denied Bowen permission to preach in the city or to move further northwards with Ilorin's protection.<ref name=\":1\" /> in 1856, Bowen returned to America. \n\nIn 1857, Bowen published an account of his mission work, which also narrated his views on how the Christian world can transform Africa. The book received attention from American's interested in African affairs and from the [[American Colonization Society]], who were already familiar with Bowen, a frequent contributor to the society's journal, American repository. \n\n<br />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:American missionaries]]\n[[Category:Christian missionaries in Nigeria]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thomas_Jefferson_Bowen"}
{"title_page": "Theresa Robinson Buck", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Theresa Robinson Buck\n| image         = File:Theresa Buck.png\n| alt           = \n| caption       = \n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1912|05|25}}\n| birth_place   = [[Hartford]], Connecticut\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|1964|09|25|1912|05|25}}\n| death_place   = [[Chikore]], Southern Rhodesia\n| nationality   = \n| other_names   = Teddy\n| occupation    = Nurse and missionary\n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = \n}}\n\n'''Theresa''' \"'''Teddy'''\" '''Robinson Buck''' (25 May 1912 \u2013 25 September 1964) was an American-born [[Southern Rhodesia]]n missionary.  She trained as a nurse in the United States before being commissioned as a missionary to Southern Rhodesia in 1938.  Buck worked in hospitals in [[Mount Selinda]] and [[Chikore]], becoming sister-in-charge of both.  After her death the Chikore hospital was renamed in her honour.\n\n== Life ==\nBorn in [[Hartford]], Connecticut on 25 May 1912, Buck was the daughter of Dr Charles Buck of [[Naples, Maine|Naples]], Maine and appears to have grown up there.<ref name=cajm>{{cite journal|title=Theresa Robinson Buck|journal=Central African Journal of Medicine|date=1 February 1967|volume=13|issue=2|page=46|url=http://journals.co.za/content/CAJM/13/2/AJA00089176_3887|language=en|issn=0008-9176}}</ref><ref name=\"shavit\">{{cite book|last1=Shavit|first1=David|title=The United States in Africa \u2013 A Historical Dictionary|date=1989|publisher=Greenwood Press|location=Westport, Connecticut|isbn=0-313-25887-2|page=32}}</ref>  At the age of 12, Buck declared that she wanted to become a nurse and a missionary.<ref name=cajm/>  She attended [[Rollins College]] in Florida and then [[Bates College]] in Maine where she majored in French.<ref name=\"shavit\"/><ref name=bates>{{cite book|title=Mirror|date=1934|publisher=Bates College|url=https://archive.org/stream/mirror193400unse/mirror193400unse_djvu.txt|p=31}}</ref>  She was active in extra-curricular societies being publicity chairman of the college's branch of the [[YWCA|Young Women's Christian Organisation]] and a member of the Christian Service Club.<ref name=bates/>  She was also active in the production of the college's yearbook, the ''Mirror'', for which she was assistant art editor in her third year and art editor in her fourth year.<ref name=bates/>  Bates was also arts editor during her fourth year of the ''Garnet'' Bates' literary and arts magazine.<ref name=bates/><ref>{{cite web|title=Constitution of the Garnet|url=http://www.bates.edu/campus/files/2013/09/Garnet-Constitution-pre-2007.pdf|archive-url=https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20151218112125/http://www.bates.edu/campus/files/2013/09/Garnet-Constitution-pre-2007.pdf|url-status=dead|archive-date=18 December 2015|publisher=Bates College|access-date=2 November 2017}}</ref>  By this time she was known as \"Teddy\" and had a reputation for being talented at art.<ref name=bates/>\n\nAfter her graduation from Bates with a [[bachelor of arts]] degree in 1934 Buck trained as a nurse at the [[Brigham and Women's Hospital|Peter Bent Brigham Hospital School of Nursing]] in Boston.<ref name=cajm/><ref>{{cite book|title=Nursing World volume 100|date=1938|page=584|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=t3cXAQAAIAAJ|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"shavit\"/>  She graduated in 1937 and became a [[Registered Nurse]].<ref name=cajm/>  At one point she was employed by the [[Brigham and Women's Hospital|Boston Lying-In Hospital]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Annual Report volumes 98\u2013110|date=1930|publisher=Boston Lying-in Hospital|page=67|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=12okAQAAMAAJ|language=en}}</ref>  Buck returned to Hartford to attend the [[Bible Normal College|Kennedy School of Missions]] and was commissioned as a missionary in March 1938.<ref name=cajm/>  This was a life appointment in the East Africa mission of the [[American Board of Commissioners for Foreign Missions]].<ref>{{cite book|title=The Missionary Herald at Home and Abroad|date=1938|publisher=Congregational churches|page=276|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=10XmAAAAMAAJ|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"shavit\"/>\n\nBuck travelled to Southern Rhodesia in late 1938, and would spend the rest of her life in the country.<ref name=\"shavit\"/>  She joined the staff of the [[Mount Selinda]] Hospital on 15 December 1938 as a nurse.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Zvobgo|first1=C. J. M.|title=A history of Christian missions in Zimbabwe, 1890\u20131939|date=1996|publisher=Mambo Press|isbn=9780869226285|page=292|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=051rAAAAIAAJ|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"shavit\"/>  She progressed to become a teacher of nursing and in 1948 was made sister-in-charge (chief administrator) of the hospital.<ref name=\"shavit\"/><ref name=cajm/><ref>{{cite book|publisher=American Board of Commissioners for Foreign Missions|title=In Him We Live and Move and Have Our Being|date=1948|work=The Board|page=7|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=dfHOAAAAMAAJ|language=en}}</ref>  In 1959 Buck was made sister-in-charge of the Cottage Hospital and Dispensary at [[Chikore]], a position she held until her death.<ref name=cajm/><ref name=\"shavit\"/>  The hospital was growing rapidly from holding an average of 10 patients at any one time in 1952 to 80 by 1962.<ref>{{cite book|title=Calendar of Prayer and Directory|publisher=United Church Board for World Ministries|page=24|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=cCMRAQAAIAAJ|language=en}}</ref>\n\nBuck died on 25 September 1964 in Chikore.<ref name=\"shavit\"/>  After her death the hospital was renamed in her honour, being referred to variously as the \"Sister Buck Memorial Hospital\" and the \"Theresa Buck Memorial Hospital\".<ref name=cajm/><ref>{{cite book|title=United Church Herald|date=1965|publisher=Joint Publication Committee of the United Church of Christ|page=32|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=FM3vAAAAMAAJ|language=en}}</ref>  The Maine Conference of the [[United Church of Christ]] donated a bell from a disused church in [[Hebron, Connecticut|Gilead]] to the Chikore Hospital Chapel in memory of Buck and later raised funds towards a new steriliser for the hospital.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Deems|first1=Mervin Monroe|title=Maine\u2014first of conferences: a history of the Maine Conference-United Church of Christ|date=1974|publisher=Furbush-Roberts Print. Co.|page=118|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=js_vAAAAMAAJ|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1912 births]]\n[[Category:1964 deaths]]\n[[Category:American missionaries]]\n[[Category:American nurses]]\n[[Category:American women nurses]]\n[[Category:Rollins College alumni]]\n[[Category:Bates College alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Hartford, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:People from Naples, Maine]]\n[[Category:White Rhodesian people]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in Rhodesia]]\n[[Category:American Protestant missionaries]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Theresa Robinson Buck\n| image         = File:Theresa Buck.png\n| alt           = \n| caption       = \n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1912|05|25}}\n| birth_place   = [[Hartford]], Connecticut\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|1964|09|25|1912|05|25}}\n| death_place   = [[Chikore]], Southern Rhodesia\n| nationality   = \n| other_names   = Teddy\n| occupation    = Nurse and missionary\n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = \n}}\n\n'''Theresa''' \"'''Teddy'''\" '''Robinson Buck''' (25 May 1912 \u2013 25 September 1964) was an American-born [[Southern Rhodesia]]n missionary.  She trained as a nurse in the United States before being commissioned as a missionary to Southern Rhodesia in 1938.  Buck worked in hospitals in [[Mount Selinda]] and [[Chikore]], becoming sister-in-charge of both.  After her death the Chikore hospital was renamed in her honour.\n\n== Life ==\nBorn in [[Hartford]], Connecticut on 25 May 1912, Buck was the daughter of Dr Charles Buck of [[Naples, Maine|Naples]], Maine and appears to have grown up there.<ref name=cajm>{{cite journal|title=Theresa Robinson Buck|journal=Central African Journal of Medicine|date=1 February 1967|volume=13|issue=2|page=46|url=http://journals.co.za/content/CAJM/13/2/AJA00089176_3887|language=en|issn=0008-9176}}</ref><ref name=\"shavit\">{{cite book|last1=Shavit|first1=David|title=The United States in Africa \u2013 A Historical Dictionary|date=1989|publisher=Greenwood Press|location=Westport, Connecticut|isbn=0-313-25887-2|page=32}}</ref>  At the age of 12, Buck declared that she wanted to become a nurse and a missionary.<ref name=cajm/>  She attended [[Rollins College]] in Florida and then [[Bates College]] in Maine where she majored in French.<ref name=\"shavit\"/><ref name=bates>{{cite book|title=Mirror|date=1934|publisher=Bates College|url=https://archive.org/stream/mirror193400unse/mirror193400unse_djvu.txt|p=31}}</ref>  She was active in extra-curricular societies being publicity chairman of the college's branch of the [[YWCA|Young Women's Christian Organisation]] and a member of the Christian Service Club.<ref name=bates/>  She was also active in the production of the college's yearbook, the ''Mirror'', for which she was assistant art editor in her third year and art editor in her fourth year.<ref name=bates/>  Bates was also arts editor during her fourth year of the ''Garnet'' Bates' literary and arts magazine.<ref name=bates/><ref>{{cite web|title=Constitution of the Garnet|url=http://www.bates.edu/campus/files/2013/09/Garnet-Constitution-pre-2007.pdf|archive-url=https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20151218112125/http://www.bates.edu/campus/files/2013/09/Garnet-Constitution-pre-2007.pdf|url-status=dead|archive-date=18 December 2015|publisher=Bates College|access-date=2 November 2017}}</ref>  By this time she was known as \"Teddy\" and had a reputation for being talented at art.<ref name=bates/>\n\nAfter her graduation from Bates with a [[bachelor of arts]] degree in 1934 Buck trained as a nurse at the [[Brigham and Women's Hospital|Peter Bent Brigham Hospital School of Nursing]] in Boston.<ref name=cajm/><ref>{{cite book|title=Nursing World volume 100|date=1938|page=584|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=t3cXAQAAIAAJ|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"shavit\"/>  She graduated in 1937 and became a [[Registered Nurse]].<ref name=cajm/>  At one point she was employed by the [[Brigham and Women's Hospital|Boston Lying-In Hospital]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Annual Report volumes 98\u2013110|date=1930|publisher=Boston Lying-in Hospital|page=67|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=12okAQAAMAAJ|language=en}}</ref>  Buck returned to Hartford to attend the [[Bible Normal College|Kennedy School of Missions]] and was commissioned as a missionary in March 1938.<ref name=cajm/>  This was a life appointment in the East Africa mission of the [[American Board of Commissioners for Foreign Missions]].<ref>{{cite book|title=The Missionary Herald at Home and Abroad|date=1938|publisher=Congregational churches|page=276|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=10XmAAAAMAAJ|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"shavit\"/>\n\nBuck travelled to Southern Rhodesia in late 1938, and would spend the rest of her life in the country.<ref name=\"shavit\"/>  She joined the staff of the [[Mount Selinda]] Hospital on 15 December 1938 as a nurse.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Zvobgo|first1=C. J. M.|title=A history of Christian missions in Zimbabwe, 1890\u20131939|date=1996|publisher=Mambo Press|isbn=9780869226285|page=292|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=051rAAAAIAAJ|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"shavit\"/>  She progressed to become a teacher of nursing and in 1948 was made sister-in-charge (chief administrator) of the hospital.<ref name=\"shavit\"/><ref name=cajm/><ref>{{cite book|publisher=American Board of Commissioners for Foreign Missions|title=In Him We Live and Move and Have Our Being|date=1948|work=The Board|page=7|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=dfHOAAAAMAAJ|language=en}}</ref>  In 1959 Buck was made sister-in-charge of the Cottage Hospital and Dispensary at [[Chikore]], a position she held until her death.<ref name=cajm/><ref name=\"shavit\"/>  The hospital was growing rapidly from holding an average of 10 patients at any one time in 1952 to 80 by 1962.<ref>{{cite book|title=Calendar of Prayer and Directory|publisher=United Church Board for World Ministries|page=24|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=cCMRAQAAIAAJ|language=en}}</ref>\n\nBuck died on 25 September 1964 in Chikore.<ref name=\"shavit\"/>  After her death the hospital was renamed in her honour, being referred to variously as the \"Sister Buck Memorial Hospital\" and the \"Theresa Buck Memorial Hospital\".<ref name=cajm/><ref>{{cite book|title=United Church Herald|date=1965|publisher=Joint Publication Committee of the United Church of Christ|page=32|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=FM3vAAAAMAAJ|language=en}}</ref>  The Maine Conference of the [[United Church of Christ]] donated a bell from a disused church in [[Hebron, Connecticut|Gilead]] to the Chikore Hospital Chapel in memory of Buck and later raised funds towards a new steriliser for the hospital.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Deems|first1=Mervin Monroe|title=Maine\u2014first of conferences: a history of the Maine Conference-United Church of Christ|date=1974|publisher=Furbush-Roberts Print. Co.|page=118|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=js_vAAAAMAAJ|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:1912 births]]\n[[Category:1964 deaths]]\n[[Category:American missionaries]]\n[[Category:American nurses]]\n[[Category:American women nurses]]\n[[Category:Rollins College alumni]]\n[[Category:Bates College alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Hartford, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:People from Naples, Maine]]\n[[Category:White Rhodesian people]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in R