{"title_page": "Teot\u00f3nio Emanuel Ribeiro Vieira de Castro", "text_new": "{{Underlinked|date=April 2020}}\n\n'''Teot\u00f3nio Emanuel Ribeiro Vieira de Castro''' was the Archbishop and Patriarch of East Indies of the Archdiocese of Goa e Dam\u00e3o, India from 1929 to 1940.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.catholic-hierarchy.org/bishop/bribe.html|title=Archbishop Teot\u00f3nio Emanuel Ribeiro Vieira de Castro [Catholic-Hierarchy]|website=www.catholic-hierarchy.org|access-date=2020-01-31}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.homemdoslivros.com/2010/02/pinto-conego-antonio-ferreira.html|title=D. Teot\u00f3nio Manuel Ribeiro Vieira de Castro|last=Duarte|first=Publicada por A.|language=pt-PT|access-date=2020-01-31}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nCastro was born in Porto, Portugal on 27 July 1859.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Priesthood ==\nOn 8 April 1882, Castro was ordained a catholic priest.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Episcopate ==\nCastro was appointed bishop of the [[Diocese of S\u00e3o Tom\u00e9 of Meliapore]] and consecrated as a bishop by Bishop Ant\u00f3nio Jos\u00e9 de Souza Barroso on 15 August 1899, in Porto, Portugal.\n\nOn 25 May 1929, he was appointed Archbishop and Patriarch of East Indies of Goa e Dam\u00e3o, India.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Death ==\nCastro died on 16 May 1940.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== References ==\n<br />\n<references />\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1859 births]]\n[[Category:1940 deaths]]\n[[Category:Portuguese missionaries]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic bishops]]\n[[Category:Archbishops]]\n[[Category:Portuguese India]]\n", "text_old": "'''Teot\u00f3nio Emanuel Ribeiro Vieira de Castro''' was the Archbishop and Patriarch of East Indies of the Archdiocese of Goa e Dam\u00e3o, India from 1929 to 1940.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.catholic-hierarchy.org/bishop/bribe.html|title=Archbishop Teot\u00f3nio Emanuel Ribeiro Vieira de Castro [Catholic-Hierarchy]|website=www.catholic-hierarchy.org|access-date=2020-01-31}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.homemdoslivros.com/2010/02/pinto-conego-antonio-ferreira.html|title=D. Teot\u00f3nio Manuel Ribeiro Vieira de Castro|last=Duarte|first=Publicada por A.|language=pt-PT|access-date=2020-01-31}}</ref>\n\n== Early Life ==\nCastro was born in Porto, Portugal on 27 July 1859.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Priesthood ==\nOn 8 April 1882, Castro was ordained a catholic priest.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Episcopate ==\nCastro was appointed bishop of the [[Diocese of S\u00e3o Tom\u00e9 of Meliapore]] and consecrated as a bishop by Bishop Ant\u00f3nio Jos\u00e9 de Souza Barroso on 15 August 1899, in Porto, Portugal.\n\nOn 25 May 1929, he was appointed Archbishop and Patriarch of East Indies of Goa e Dam\u00e3o, India.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Death ==\nCastro died on 16 May 1940.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== References ==\n<br />\n<references />\n[[Category:1859 births]]\n[[Category:1940 deaths]]\n[[Category:Portuguese missionaries]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic bishops]]\n[[Category:Archbishops]]\n[[Category:Portuguese India]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control, addedunderlinkedtag", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Teot%C3%B3nio_Emanuel_Ribeiro_Vieira_de_Castro"}
{"title_page": "Tariq Jamil", "text_new": "{{Use British English Oxford spelling|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox religious biography\n| name               = Tariq Jamil\n| birth_name         = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1953|1|1|df=y}}\n| birth_place        = [[Mian Channu]], [[Khanewal]], [[Punjab]], [[Pakistan]]\n| religion = [[Islam]]\n| denomination = [[Sunni Islam|Sunni]]\n| residence          = \n| other_names        = \n| nationality        = {{flag|Pakistan|name=Pakistani}}\n| alma_mater         = Jamia Arabia, [[Raiwind]]\n| occupation         = \n| movement       = [[Tablighi Jamaat]]\n| known_for          = \n| home_town          = \n| salary             = \n| net_worth          = <!-- Net worth should be supported with a citation from a reliable source -->\n| television         = \n| spouse             = <!-- Use article title or common name -->\n| children           = \n| parents            = <!-- overrides mother and father parameters -->\n| relatives          = \n| family             = \n| awards             = \n| website            = {{url|tariqjamilofficial.com}} \n| signature          = \n| module2            = {{Infobox YouTube personality | embed = yes\n| name =\n| channel_direct_url = channel/UCct5L-DaVYK8UtmqGU8gJtw\n| subscribers        = 3.38 million\n| subscriber_date    = 13 April 2020\n| views              = 211 million\n| view_date          = 13 April 2020\n| years_active       = 2017\u2013present\n| gold_button        = yes\n| gold_year          = 2019\n| stats_update       = 13 April 2020\n}}}}\n'''Tariq Jamil''' ({{lang-ur|{{Nastaliq|\u0637\u0627\u0631\u0642 \u062c\u0645\u06cc\u0644}}}}; born 1 October 1953) is a Pakistani Islamic television preacher, religious writer, scholar and a member of the [[Tablighi Jamaat]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/urdu/pakistan-48332315|title=\u0628\u0691\u06d2 \u06c1\u0648 \u06a9\u0631 \u06a9\u06cc\u0627 \u0628\u0646\u0648 \u06af\u06d2\u060c \u0645\u0648\u0644\u0627\u0646\u0627 \u0637\u0627\u0631\u0642 \u062c\u0645\u06cc\u0644|trans-title=Q: What Do You Want To Be When You Grow Up, A: Maulana Tariq Jamil|first=Muhammad|last=Hanif|date=20 May 2019|website=BBC Urdu}}</ref><ref name=Ulrike326>{{cite book |editor1-first=Ulrike |editor1-last=Freitag |title=Translocality: The Study of Globalising Processes from a Southern Perspective |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=M6_VjCY7rSMC&pg=PA326 |accessdate=30 October 2014 |year=2009 |publisher=BRILL |location= |isbn=9789004181168 |page=326}}</ref><ref name=\"themuslim500\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.themuslim500.com/profiles/maulana-tariq-jameel/|title=Maulana Tariq Jameel |website=The Muslim 500|access-date=2019-04-03}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nTariq Jamil was born on 1 January 1953 in [[Mian Channu]], Pakistan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://jang.com.pk/amp/11818|title=\u0645\u0648\u0644\u0627\u0646\u0627 \u0637\u0627\u0631\u0642 \u062c\u0645\u06cc\u0644 \u0627\u0648\u0631 \u0639\u0627\u0645\u0631 \u062e\u0627\u0646\u06d4\u06d4\u06d4\u062f\u0648\u0631\u0650 \u0646\u0648|trans-title=Maulana Tariq Jamil and [[Aamir Khan]]...New era|first=Ali Moeen|last=Nawazish|authorlink=Ali Moeen Nawazish|date=28 November 2013|website=[[Daily Jang]]}}</ref> Jamil is an alumnus of [[Government College University (Lahore)|Government College University, Lahore]]. He received his Islamic education from Jamia Arabia, [[Raiwind]], where he studied [[Quran|Qur\u2019an]], [[Hadith]], [[Sufism]], [[mantiq|logic]], and [[Islamic jurisprudence]].<ref name=\"themuslim500\"/>\n\n== Career ==\nTariq Jamil has delivered religious sermons internationally and comes from a school of thought called [[Deobandi|Deoband]].<ref>{{cite book |editor1-first=Dietrich |editor1-last= Reetz |title=Islam in Europa: Religi\u00f6ses Leben heute |language=German |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wuX_fdK5XYcC&pg=PA49 |accessdate=30 October 2014 |year=2010 |publisher= Waxmann Verlag |isbn= 9783830973812 |page=49}}</ref> He supports ethnic and sectarian harmony.<ref name=\"ExpressTribune1\">{{cite news |title=Tablighi cleric's political meetings raise eyebrows |url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/236730/tablighi-clerics-political-meetings-raise-eyebrows/  |accessdate=31 October 2014|newspaper=The Express Tribune|date=22 August 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"ExpressTribune2\">{{cite news |title=Religious harmony: Dousing the flames of sectarianism |url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/561499/religious-harmony-dousing-the-flames-of-sectarianism/|accessdate=31 October 2014|newspaper=The Express Tribune|date=11 June 2013}}</ref>\n\nJamil's sermons focus on \"self-purification, avoidance of violence, observance of Allah\u2019s orders and pursuing the way of Prophet [[Muhammad]].\"<ref name=\"themuslim500\"/>\n\nJamil has been named continuously as one as of [[The 500 Most Influential Muslims]] in the world by the [[Royal Aal al-Bayt Institute for Islamic Thought]] in [[Jordan]] from 2013 to 2019.<ref name=\"themuslim500\"/>\n\n==Relationship with influencers==\nJamil enjoys good terms with [[Sharif family]] and [[:Category:Chaudhry family|Chaudhry family of Gujrat]], particularly [[Chaudhry Pervaiz Elahi]].<ref name=\"newslinemagazine/1\">{{cite news |title=A Maulana For All Seasons? |url=https://newslinemagazine.com/magazine/a-maulana-for-all-seasons/ |accessdate=8 April 2020 |work=Newsline |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n* Tariq Jamil, ''Majmua Bayanat-e-Jameel'' (2014) {{ISBN|9-691-19936-X}}\n* Tariq Jamil, ''Hamare Masail Ka Hal'' (2014) {{ISBN|9-697-37895-9}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official|https://www.tariqjamilofficial.com/ }}\n\n{{Tablighi Jamaat}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jamil, Tariq}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:Tablighi Jamaat people]]\n[[Category:Pakistani Islamic religious leaders]]\n[[Category:Pakistani Sunni Muslim scholars