{"title_page": "Swami Ghanananda (Ghana)", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n|image         =\n|name          = Swami Ghanananda\n|birth_place   = Senya Beraku, [[Central Region, Ghana|Central Region]], [[Ghana]]\n|birth_date    = {{birth date|1937|9|12|df=yes}}\n|death_date    = {{Death date and age|2016|1|18|1937|9|12|df=yes}}\n|death_place   = \n|occupation    = [[Swami]]<br /> [[Guru-shishya tradition|\u015aishya]] of [[Swami Krishnananda]]\n}}\n'''Swami Ghanananda''' (12 September 1937 \u2013 18 January 2016) \u0b9a\u0bbe\u0bae\u0bbf \u0b95\u0bbe\u0ba9\u0bbe\u0ba9\u0ba8\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bbe) is a prominent swami of the indigenous [[Hinduism in Ghana|Hindu community in Ghana]], and is the first{{citation needed|date=July 2014}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.myjoyonline.com/news/2016/february-2nd/guide-kwesi-essel-first-african-hindu-monk-dies.php|title=Ghana News - Swami Saraswati, first African Hindu monk from Ghana, dies|last=Myjoyonline.com|website=www.myjoyonline.com|access-date=2016-06-16}}</ref> Hindu swami of African ancestry. He was initiated as a [[swami]] by the late [[Swami Krishnananda]] of India in 1975, and was head the Hindu Monastery of Africa in [[Accra]], Ghana.<ref name=\"Ghana's unique African-Hindu\">[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/south_asia/10401741.stm Ghana's unique African-Hindu temple - BBC News] By [[Rajesh Joshi]]</ref>\n\n==Biography==\n===Early life===\nSwami Ghanananda was born in a Senya Beraku village, [[Central Region, Ghana|central region]] of Ghana on 12 September into a native Ghanaian faith, but his parents converted to Christianity. From a very early age he thought about the mysteries of the universe and tried to find the answers in religious texts.<ref name=\"Ghana's unique African-Hindu\"/>\n\n===Journey to India===\nSwami Ghanananda then read some books on the Hindu faith and embarked upon a new journey which took him to [[Rishikesh]] in the [[India]]n [[States and territories of India|state]] of [[Uttarakhand]] in northern India. He spent some time there with a spiritual guru who suggested him to open the monastery in Accra.<ref name=\"Ghana's unique African-Hindu\"/>\n\n===First meeting with Swami Krishnananda===\nIn 1962, Swami Ghanananda moved to Accra and on 24 November, he formed the Divine Mystic Path Society. He then started correspondence courses on the Hindu way of life ([[Sanatana Dharma#Dharma|Sanatana Dharma]]) with the Divine Life Society of Rishikesh, located in the foothills of the [[Himalaya]]s in northern India, where he first met [[Swami Krishnananda]] of India and became his [[Guru-shishya tradition|\u015bishya]] (disciple), and then in 1975 Swami Krishnananda initiated Swami Ghanananda as a [[swami]].<ref name=\"Ghana's unique African-Hindu\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/world/south_asia/10401741.stm Ghana's unique African-Hindu temple] at [[BBC News]]\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ghanananda}}\n[[Category:Hindu monks|Ghanananda, Swami]]\n[[Category:Converts to Hinduism|Ghanananda, Swami]]\n[[Category:Hindu missionaries]]\n[[Category:Hinduism in Ghana]]\n[[Category:Ghanaian Hindus]]\n[[Category:1937 births]]\n[[Category:Ghanaian monks]]\n[[Category:Ghanaian missionaries]]\n[[Category:2016 deaths]]\n\n\n{{Hindu-bio-stub}}\n{{Africa-reli-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n|image         =\n|name          = Swami Ghanananda\n|birth_place   = Senya Beraku, [[Central Region, Ghana|Central Region]], [[Ghana]]\n|birth_date    = {{birth date|1937|9|12|df=yes}}\n|death_date    = {{Death date and age|2016|1|18|1937|9|12|df=yes}}\n|death_place   = \n|occupation    = [[Swami]]<br /> [[Guru-shishya tradition|\u015aishya]] of [[Swami Krishnananda]]\n}}\n'''Swami Ghanananda''' (12 September 1937 \u2013 18 January 2016) \u0b9a\u0bbe\u0bae\u0bbf \u0b95\u0bbe\u0ba9\u0bbe\u0ba9\u0ba8\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bbe) is a prominent swami of the indigenous [[Hinduism in Ghana|Hindu community in Ghana]], and is the first{{citation needed|date=July 2014}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.myjoyonline.com/news/2016/february-2nd/guide-kwesi-essel-first-african-hindu-monk-dies.php|title=Ghana News - Swami Saraswati, first African Hindu monk from Ghana, dies|last=Myjoyonline.com|website=www.myjoyonline.com|access-date=2016-06-16}}</ref> Hindu swami of African ancestry. He was initiated as a [[swami]] by the late [[Swami Krishnananda]] of India in 1975, and was head the Hindu Monastery of Africa in [[Accra]], Ghana.<ref name=\"Ghana's unique African-Hindu\">[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/south_asia/10401741.stm Ghana's unique African-Hindu temple - BBC News] By [[Rajesh Joshi]]</ref>\n\n==Biography==\n===Early life===\nSwami Ghanananda was born in a Senya Beraku village, [[Central Region, Ghana|central region]] of Ghana on 12 September into a native Ghanaian faith, but his parents converted to Christianity. From a very early age he thought about the mysteries of the universe and tried to find the answers in religious texts.<ref name=\"Ghana's unique African-Hindu\"/>\n\n===Journey to India===\nSwami Ghanananda then read some books on the Hindu faith and embarked upon a new journey which took him to [[Rishikesh]] in the [[India]]n [[States and territories of India|state]] of [[Uttarakhand]] in northern India. He spent some time there with a spiritual guru who suggested him to open the monastery in Accra.<ref name=\"Ghana's unique African-Hindu\"/>\n\n===First meeting with Swami Krishnananda===\nIn 1962, Swami Ghanananda moved to Accra and on 24 November, he formed the Divine Mystic Path Society. He then started correspondence courses on the Hindu way of life ([[Sanatana_Dharma#Dharma|Sanatana Dharma]]) with the Divine Life Society of Rishikesh, located in the foothills of the [[Himalaya]]s in northern India, where he first met [[Swami Krishnananda]] of India and became his [[Guru-shishya tradition|\u015bishya]] (disciple), and then in 1975 Swami Krishnananda initiated Swami Ghanananda as a [[swami]].<ref name=\"Ghana's unique African-Hindu\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/world/south_asia/10401741.stm Ghana's unique African-Hindu temple] at [[BBC News]]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ghanananda}}\n[[Category:Hindu monks|Ghanananda, Swami]]\n[[Category:Converts to Hinduism|Ghanananda, Swami]]\n[[Category:Hindu missionaries]]\n[[Category:Hinduism in Ghana]]\n[[Category:Ghanaian Hindus]]\n[[Category:1937 births]]\n[[Category:Ghanaian monks]]\n[[Category:Ghanaian missionaries]]\n[[Category:2016 deaths]]\n\n\n{{Hindu-bio-stub}}\n{{Africa-reli-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Swami_Ghanananda_(Ghana)"}
{"title_page": "Stanley Gordon Sturges", "text_new": "{{short description|American physician and missionary}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Stanley Gordon Sturges\n| image              =\n| image_size         = 250px\n| caption            = Stanley and Raylene Sturges\n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = October 14, 1929\n| birth_place        = Congo\n| death_date         = July 12, 2019\n| death_place        = Portland, Oregon\n| nationality        = American\n| alma_mater         = Pacific Union College \u201950, \nLoma Linda College of Medical Evangelists \u201955\n| occupation         = Seventh-Day Adventist Medical Missionary\n| honours            = 1961 Ten Outstanding Young Americans\n}}\n'''Stanley Gordon Sturges''' (October 14, 1929 - July 12, 2019) was an American physician and missionary.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=In the Valley of Seven Cities|last=Sturges|first=Stanley|publisher=Review and Herald Pub. Association|year=1965|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> He and his wife, Raylene Sturges, were the first [[Seventh-day Adventist Church|Seventh-day Adventist]] medical missionaries to Nepal in 1957. They founded the [[Scheer Memorial Adventist Hospital|Scheer Memorial Hospital]] in [[Banepa]], which is the only Western hospital in [[Kavrepalanchok District|Kavre District]] and serves half a million people.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.scheermemhosp.org/|title=Scheer Memorial Adventist Hospital|website=Scheer Memorial Adventist Hospital|language=en|access-date=2019-12-11}}</ref> In 1961, the [[Junior Chamber of Commerce|US Junior Chamber of Commerce]] named Sturges one of [[Ten Outstanding Young Persons of the World|Ten Outstanding Young Americans]].<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.citynewsgroup.com/articles/e0c13848ccf9eb48e48a47d238a84fee|title=Heritage Snapshot Part 205: Stanley G. Sturges MD|website=www.citynewsgroup.com|language=en|access-date=2019-12-11}}</ref>\n\nSturges came from a strong tradition of medical missionary work in his family, and his goal was to minister to the needs of the sick and needy disregarding their social or economic position. It was illegal to openly speak and preach Christianity in Nepal at the time, so patients would come into contact with Sturges\u2019 religion through the hospital.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sturges|first=Stanley|date=July\u2013August 1962|title=To Give His Very Best|url=http://documents.adventistarchives.org/Periodicals/LISTEN/LISTEN19620701-V15-04.pdf|journal=Listen Journal of Better Living|volume=15|pages=|via=Adventist Archives}}</ref>\n\n== Family, Education, and Early Life ==\nSturges was born in Congo on October 14, 1929 to medical missionary parents.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://obits.oregonlive.com/obituaries/oregon/obituary.aspx?n=stanley-g-sturges&pid=193490345|title=Stanley G. Sturges|last=The Oregonian|date=July 28, 2019|website=Oregon Obituaries|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=December 10, 2019}}</ref> His father, Dr. [[J. Hubert Sturges]] had a medical practice for the Seventh-Day Adventist Church in Congo. He had an older brother, Dr. [[Hubert F. Sturges]] who opened a missionary practice in Ethiopia and a younger brother, Dr. [[Keith W. Sturges]] who eventually took over the Scheer Memorial Hospital. His sister, Elizabeth Taylor was also a medical missionary in Kenya.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nSturges grew up in California where he and his brothers were taught manual work, such as carpentry and painting. Sturges later wrote that education was a priority in his family and that mission work was his goal from childhood.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nHe received a B.A. degree from [[Pacific Union College]], where he was the student body president.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.puc.edu/__data/assets/pdf_file/0009/159660/ViewPoint-38.4.pdf|title=ViewPoint Pacific Union College|last=Pacific Union College|date=2016|website=Pacific Union College|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=December 10, 2019}}</ref> Later, he enrolled at [[Loma Linda University|Loma Linda University Medical School]] as a medical student.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://library.llu.edu/sturges-stanley-g-raylene|title=Sturges, Stanley G. & Raylene {{!}} Loma Linda University Libraries|website=library.llu.edu|access-date=2019-12-11}}</ref>\n\n=== Volleyball ===\nSturges played for the 1955 Loma Linda university volleyball team that went on to win second place at the national championship. It was the only organized sports program the university ever had. After beating big-name universities in the Los Angeles area and qualifying for the National Tournament, his team came within 2 points of winning the national championship against Florida State University. Sturges was named to the 1955 All-American team for the Collegiate Division.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://drayson.llu.edu/about/drayson-news/loma-linda-university-naia-division-ii-mens-volleyball-team-loses-florida-state-finals|title=Loma Linda University NAIA Division II Men's Volleyball Team Loses to Florida State in Finals {{!}} Drayson Center {{!}} Loma Linda University|website=drayson.llu.edu|access-date=2019-12-11}}</ref>\n\n== Medical Mission ==\n\n=== Banepa Practice ===\nTwo years after graduating from medical school, Sturges arrived in Nepal with his two children and wife, Raylene Sturges in 1957. The Seventh Day Adventist Church supported their mission, and Sturges later wrote in his autobiography that his \u201cmotivation to enter mission service centered chiefly in the desire to witness in a practical way to the love of Christ for all.\u201d<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nSturges originally planned to open a practice in Kathmandu, but didn\u2019t want to threaten the United Medical Mission already serving there, so he looked 16 miles east to Banepa. Back then, Banepa was a district center of nearly a 1/4 million people without regular service of a doctor. It was the hub of three trade routes converging on the Valley of Seven Cities, also known as the [[Kathmandu Valley]]. When he passed through the city, headsman and 10,000 of local tribesman staged a demonstration for Sturges to choose the city for his practice.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://documents.adventistarchives.org/Periodicals/RH/RH19620111-V139-02.pdf|title=Medical Missionary Given High Honor|last=Moore|first=Raymond|date=January 11, 1962|work=Review and Herald|access-date=December 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe first clinic was opened in a run-down second-floor rented room. Problems plagued the practice, such as the shortage of medicine supply and reluctance of people to come in. Sturges hired more staff and eventually started treating up to 100 patients daily. His wife often helped out and filled in for Sturges when he wasn\u2019t around.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Scheer Memorial Hospital ===\n[[File:Scheer_Memorial_Hospital.jpg|alt=|right|285x285px|Scheer Memorial Hospital in Banepa, Nepal]]\nThrough the alumni network at Loma Linda University, Sturges contacted Clifford C. Scheer, a construction consultant in New Jersey who was thinking about constructing a memorial for his recently deceased parents. Scheer donated $25,000 for the creation of the [[Scheer Memorial Adventist Hospital|Carolyn and Charles J. Scheer Memorial Hospital]] of Seventh-Day Adventists.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nSturges and community members built the hospital themselves over one and a half years. It was officially opened and dedicated in a ceremony on May 18, 1959, which was attended by former Prime Minister [[BP Koirala]], the Minister of Health, and 3,000 townsmen.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe hospital, originally a 20-bed facility serving 100 patients daily, has now evolved into a three-story, 150-bed facility. It has also since established the Scheer Memorial Adventists Hospital Medical Institute, College of Nursing where students can earn a B. Sc. Nursing degree and get clinical practice.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nBecause of the abundance of patients, Sturges also opened mobile clinics in [[Panauti]] and [[Dapcha Chhatrebangh|Dapcha Chhaatrebangh]] on different days of the week.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Problems Encountered ===\nSturges treated a range of diseases, including [[cholera]], [[tuberculosis]], [[elephantiasis]], [[malaria]], [[Typhoid fever|typhoid]], and [[smallpox]]. In addition to the lack of electricity and modern tools, Sturges faced wide-spread taboos in the village. such as how male physicians couldn\u2019t examine women.<ref>{{Cite news|title=U.S. Medical Missionary Mixes Healing and Fellowship in Nepal|last=Wicklein|first=John|date=January 28, 1962|work=The New York Times|id={{ProQuest|115967775}}}}</ref>\n\nA local pressed charges against Sturges and the hospital, insinuating that the hospital blocked a nearby holy water source, destroyed a path connecting [[Banepa]] to [[Chandeshwari|Chandeswori]], overcharged for services, preached the Christian religion openly, and that Sturges was guilty of malpractice. The village people, however, rebuked his charges and laughed him out of court.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Legacy ==\nIn 1961, Sturges was named one of [[Ten Outstanding Young Persons of the World|America\u2019s Outstanding Young Men]] by the [[Junior Chamber of Commerce|US Junior Chamber of Commerce]].<ref name=\":2\" /> The ceremony was broadcast on national television on January 20, 1961, and Sturges appeared on the [[The Ed Sullivan Show|Ed Sullivan show]], [[Today (American TV program)|the Today show]], and met President [[Richard Nixon]].<ref name=\":3\" /> He was also featured in [[Life (magazine)|Life Magazine]]\u2019s September 14, 1962 special issue of \u201c100 Outstanding Members of the Take-Over Generation.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=z00EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA5&lpg=PA5&dq=stanley+sturges+medical+missionary&source=bl&ots=lE383BrN-h&sig=ACfU3U0jmnSOaBJjRvdgnBg8gCknJK4YbQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiiod3nn8DlAhWQiOAKHSepD28Q6AEwCHoECAkQAQ#v=onepage&q=stanley%20sturges%20medical%20missionary&f=false|title=One Hundred of the Most Important Young Men and Women in the United States|last=Life Magazine|first=|date=September 14, 1962|work=LIFE|access-date=December 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\nSturges received the [[Academy of Achievement|American Academy of Achievement Golden Plate Award]] in 1965<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.afb.org/HelenKellerArchive?a=d&d=A-HK01-05-B096-F02-002.1.3|title=The 1965 Banquet of the Golden Plate Program mailed to Helen Keller.|last=|first=|date=1965|website=American Foundation for the Blind|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=December 10, 2019}}</ref> and the Pacific Union College Honored Alumnus Award in 2016.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n== Personal life ==\nSturges had four children with Raylene Sturges. His fourth child, Cheri, was delivered in a station wagon on the way to [[Kathmandu]] in 1960.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nSturges and his wife were very involved in the Seventh Day Adventist Church. Sturges contributed to their quarterly journal, writing a piece titled \u201cEllen White\u2019s Authority and the Church\u201d in the summer 1972 issue.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sturges|first=Stanley|date=Summer 1972|title=Ellen White's Authority and the Church|url=https://www.andrews.edu/library/car/cardigital/Periodicals/Spectrum/1972_Vol_4/3_Summer.pdf|journal=The Spectrum: Adventist Focum|volume=4|pages=|via=Andrews University}}</ref>\n\nUpon returning to the United States, Sturges was an instructor in psychiatry at the [[University of Cincinnati]] before retiring in [[Portland, Oregon|Portland]], Oregon. During retirement, he was affiliated with the [[Adventist Health Portland|Adventist Medical Center-Portland]], and [[Legacy Good Samaritan Medical Center]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://health.usnews.com/doctors/stanley-sturges-929809|title=Dr. Stanley Sturges|last=|first=|date=|website=US News|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=December 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\nSturges died on July 12, 2019 in Portland, Oregon.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.crowncremationburial.com/obituaries/obituary/17292_Stanley_Gordon_Sturges|title=Stanley Gordon Sturges|last=|first=|date=|website=www.crowncremationburial.com|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-11}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Medical missionaries]]\n[[Category:Missionaries]]\n[[Category:American missionaries]]\n[[Category:1929 births]]\n[[Category:2019 deaths]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American physician and missionary}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Stanley Gordon Sturges\n| image              =\n| image_size         = 250px\n| caption            = Stanley and Raylene Sturges\n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = October 14, 1929\n| birth_place        = Congo\n| death_date         = July 12, 2019\n| death_place        = Portland, Oregon\n| nationality        = American\n| alma_mater         = Pacific Union College \u201950, \nLoma Linda College of Medical Evangelists \u201955\n| occupation         = Seventh-Day Adventist Medical Missionary\n| honours            = 1961 Ten Outstanding Young Americans\n}}\n'''Stanley Gordon Sturges''' (October 14, 1929 - July 12, 2019) was an American physician and missionary.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=In the Valley of Seven Cities|last=Sturges|first=Stanley|publisher=Review and Herald Pub. Association|year=1965|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> He and his wife, Raylene Sturges, were the first [[Seventh-day Adventist Church|Seventh-day Adventist]] medical missionaries to Nepal in 1957. They founded the [[Scheer Memorial Adventist Hospital|Scheer Memorial Hospital]] in [[Banepa]], which is the only Western hospital in [[Kavrepalanchok District|Kavre District]] and serves half a million people.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.scheermemhosp.org/|title=Scheer Memorial Adventist Hospital|website=Scheer Memorial Adventist Hospital|language=en|access-date=2019-12-11}}</ref> In 1961, the [[Junior Chamber of Commerce|US Junior Chamber of Commerce]] named Sturges one of [[Ten Outstanding Young Persons of the World|Ten Outstanding Young Americans]].<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.citynewsgroup.com/articles/e0c13848ccf9eb48e48a47d238a84fee|title=Heritage Snapshot Part 205: Stanley G. Sturges MD|website=www.citynewsgroup.com|language=en|access-date=2019-12-11}}</ref>\n\nSturges came from a strong tradition of medical missionary work in his family, and his goal was to minister to the needs of the sick and needy disregarding their social or economic position. It was illegal to openly speak and preach Christianity in Nepal at the time, so patients would come into contact with Sturges\u2019 religion through the hospital.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sturges|first=Stanley|date=July-August 1962|title=To Give His Very Best|url=http://documents.adventistarchives.org/Periodicals/LISTEN/LISTEN19620701-V15-04.pdf|journal=Listen Journal of Better Living|volume=15|pages=|via=Adventist Archives}}</ref>\n\n== Family, Education, and Early Life ==\nSturges was born in Congo on October 14, 1929 to medical missionary parents.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://obits.oregonlive.com/obituaries/oregon/obituary.aspx?n=stanley-g-sturges&pid=193490345|title=Stanley G. Sturges|last=The Oregonian|date=July 28, 2019|website=Oregon Obituaries|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=December 10, 2019}}</ref> His father, Dr. [[J. Hubert Sturges]] had a medical practice for the Seventh-Day Adventist Church in Congo. He had an older brother, Dr. [[Hubert F. Sturges]] who opened a missionary practice in Ethiopia and a younger brother, Dr. [[Keith W. Sturges]] who eventually took over the Scheer Memorial Hospital. His sister, Elizabeth Taylor was also a medical missionary in Kenya.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nSturges grew up in California where he and his brothers were taught manual work, such as carpentry and painting. Sturges later wrote that education was a priority in his family and that mission work was his goal from childhood.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nHe received a B.A. degree from [[Pacific Union College]], where he was the student body president.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.puc.edu/__data/assets/pdf_file/0009/159660/ViewPoint-38.4.pdf|title=ViewPoint Pacific Union College|last=Pacific Union College|date=2016|website=Pacific Union College|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=December 10, 2019}}</ref> Later, he enrolled at [[Loma Linda University|Loma Linda University Medical School]] as a medical student.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://library.llu.edu/sturges-stanley-g-raylene|title=Sturges, Stanley G. & Raylene {{!}} Loma Linda University Libraries|website=library.llu.edu|access-date=2019-12-11}}</ref>\n\n=== Volleyball ===\nSturges played for the 1955 Loma Linda university volleyball team that went on to win second place at the national championship. It was the only organized sports program the university ever had. After beating big-name universities in the Los Angeles area and qualifying for the National Tournament, his team came within 2 points of winning the national championship against Florida State University. Sturges was named to the 1955 All-American team for the Collegiate Division.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://drayson.llu.edu/about/drayson-news/loma-linda-university-naia-division-ii-mens-volleyball-team-loses-florida-state-finals|title=Loma Linda University NAIA Division II Men's Volleyball Team Loses to Florida State in Finals {{!}} Drayson Center {{!}} Loma Linda University|website=drayson.llu.edu|access-date=2019-12-11}}</ref>\n\n== Medical Mission ==\n\n=== Banepa Practice ===\nTwo years after graduating from medical school, Sturges arrived in Nepal with his two children and wife, Raylene Sturges in 1957. The Seventh Day Adventist Church supported their mission, and Sturges later wrote in his autobiography that his \u201cmotivation to enter mission service centered chiefly in the desire to witness in a practical way to the love of Christ for all.\u201d<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nSturges originally planned to open a practice in Kathmandu, but didn\u2019t want to threaten the United Medical Mission already serving there, so he looked 16 miles east to Banepa. Back then, Banepa was a district center of nearly a 1/4 million people without regular service of a doctor. It was the hub of three trade routes converging on the Valley of Seven Cities, also known as the [[Kathmandu Valley]]. When he passed through the city, headsman and 10,000 of local tribesman staged a demonstration for Sturges to choose the city for his practice.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://documents.adventistarchives.org/Periodicals/RH/RH19620111-V139-02.pdf|title=Medical Missionary Given High Honor|last=Moore|first=Raymond|date=January 11, 1962|work=Review and Herald|access-date=December 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe first clinic was opened in a run-down second-floor rented room. Problems plagued the practice, such as the shortage of medicine supply and reluctance of people to come in. Sturges hired more staff and eventually started treating up to 100 patients daily. His wife often helped out and filled in for Sturges when he wasn\u2019t around.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Scheer Memorial Hospital ===\n[[File:Scheer_Memorial_Hospital.jpg|alt=|right|285x285px|Scheer Memorial Hospital in Banepa, Nepal]]\nThrough the alumni network at Loma Linda University, Sturges contacted Clifford C. Scheer, a construction consultant in New Jersey who was thinking about constructing a memorial for his recently deceased parents. Scheer donated $25,000 for the creation of the [[Scheer Memorial Adventist Hospital|Carolyn and Charles J. Scheer Memorial Hospital]] of Seventh-Day Adventists.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nSturges and community members built the hospital themselves over one and a half years. It was officially opened and dedicated in a ceremony on May 18, 1959, which was attended by former Prime Minister [[BP Koirala]], the Minister of Health, and 3,000 townsmen.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe hospital, originally a 20-bed facility serving 100 patients daily, has now evolved into a three-story, 150-bed facility. It has also since established the Scheer Memorial Adventists Hospital Medical Institute, College of Nursing where students can earn a B. Sc. Nursing degree and get clinical practice.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nBecause of the abundance of patients, Sturges also opened mobile clinics in [[Panauti]] and [[Dapcha Chhatrebangh|Dapcha Chhaatrebangh]] on different days of the week.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Problems Encountered ===\nSturges treated a range of diseases, including [[cholera]], [[tuberculosis]], [[elephantiasis]], [[malaria]], [[Typhoid fever|typhoid]], and [[smallpox]]. In addition to the lack of electricity and modern tools, Sturges faced wide-spread taboos in the village. such as how male physicians couldn\u2019t examine women.<ref>{{Cite news|title=U.S. Medical Missionary Mixes Healing and Fellowship in Nepal|last=Wicklein|first=John|date=January 28, 1962|work=The New York Times|id={{ProQuest|115967775}}}}</ref>\n\nA local pressed charges against Sturges and the hospital, insinuating that the hospital blocked a nearby holy water source, destroyed a path connecting [[Banepa]] to [[Chandeshwari|Chandeswori]], overcharged for services, preached the Christian religion openly, and that Sturges was guilty of malpractice. The village people, however, rebuked his charges and laughed him out of court.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Legacy ==\nIn 1961, Sturges was named one of [[Ten Outstanding Young Persons of the World|America\u2019s Outstanding Young Men]] by the [[Junior Chamber of Commerce|US Junior Chamber of Commerce]].<ref name=\":2\" /> The ceremony was broadcast on national television on January 20, 1961, and Sturges appeared on the [[The Ed Sullivan Show|Ed Sullivan show]], [[Today (American TV program)|the Today show]], and met President [[Richard Nixon]].<ref name=\":3\" /> He was also featured in [[Life (magazine)|Life Magazine]]\u2019s September 14, 1962 special issue of \u201c100 Outstanding Members of the Take-Over Generation.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=z00EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA5&lpg=PA5&dq=stanley+sturges+medical+missionary&source=bl&ots=lE383BrN-h&sig=ACfU3U0jmnSOaBJjRvdgnBg8gCknJK4YbQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiiod3nn8DlAhWQiOAKHSepD28Q6AEwCHoECAkQAQ#v=onepage&q=stanley%20sturges%20medical%20missionary&f=false|title=One Hundred of the Most Important Young Men and Women in the United States|last=Life Magazine|first=|date=September 14, 1962|work=LIFE|access-date=December 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\nSturges received the [[Academy of Achievement|American Academy of Achievement Golden Plate Award]] in 1965<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.afb.org/HelenKellerArchive?a=d&d=A-HK01-05-B096-F02-002.1.3|title=The 1965 Banquet of the Golden Plate Program mailed to Helen Keller.|last=|first=|date=1965|website=American Foundation for the Blind|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=December 10, 2019}}</ref> and the Pacific Union College Honored Alumnus Award in 2016.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n== Personal Life ==\nSturges had four children with Raylene Sturges. His fourth child, Cheri, was delivered in a station wagon on the way to [[Kathmandu]] in 1960.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nSturges and his wife were very involved in the Seventh Day Adventist Church. Sturges contributed to their quarterly journal, writing a piece titled \u201cEllen White\u2019s Authority and the Church\u201d in the summer 1972 issue.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sturges|first=Stanley|date=Summer 1972|title=Ellen White's Authority and the Church|url=https://www.andrews.edu/library/car/cardigital/Periodicals/Spectrum/1972_Vol_4/3_Summer.pdf|journal=The Spectrum: Adventist Focum|volume=4|pages=|via=Andrews University}}</ref>\n\nUpon returning to the United States, Sturges was an instructor in psychiatry at the [[University of Cincinnati]] before retiring in [[Portland, Oregon|Portland]], Oregon. During retirement, he was affiliated with the [[Adventist Health Portland|Adventist Medical Center-Portland]], and [[Legacy Good Samaritan Medical Center]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://health.usnews.com/doctors/stanley-sturges-929809|title=Dr. Stanley Sturges|last=|first=|date=|website=US News|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=December 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\nSturges died on July 12, 2019 in Portland, Oregon.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.crowncremationburial.com/obituaries/obituary/17292_Stanley_Gordon_Sturges|title=Stanley Gordon Sturges|last=|first=|date=|website=www.crowncremationburial.com|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-11}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n[[Category:Medical missionaries]]\n[[Category:Missionaries]]\n[[Category:American missionaries]]\n[[Category:1929 births]]\n[[Category:2019 deaths]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stanley_Gordon_Sturges"}
{"title_page": "Shri Krishna Sharma", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=October 2016}}\n'''[[Pandit]] Shri Krishna Sharma''' was an [[Arya Samaj]] preacher who came to [[Fiji]] in 1926 from [[Rajkot]], [[India]]. He was a gifted public speaker and singer of religious songs. He provided impetus to the Arya Samaj movement in Fiji. Under his influence Arya Samaj schools and temples were established in Fiji. He was responsible for the establishment of the ''[[Hindu Maha Sabha (Fiji)|Hindu Maha Sabha]]'' for the purpose of uniting all [[Hindus]] in Fiji. He advocated ''[[shuddhi]]'' (reconversion to Hinduism) and this caused conflict with [[Muslim]]s and [[Christians]] in Fiji.\n\nSharma also started a monthly Hindi language newspaper called the ''Vedic Sandesh''.<ref name=\"Kanwal1980\">{{cite book |last=Kanwal |first=J. S. |authorlink= |title=A Hundred years of Hindi in Fiji  |year=1980 |publisher=Fiji Teachers Union |location=Suva, Fiji |isbn=| page= 92 }}</ref>\n\nHe returned to India in 1929 and the Government of Fiji refused permission for him to return to Fiji.\n\nIn 1956, he returned to Fiji to participate in the [[Golden Jubilee]] of the Arya Samaj in Fiji. He founded the [[Dayanand Anglo-Vedic Schools System|D.A.V. College]] in [[Suva]] and an Arya temple in [[Nadi]].<ref name=\"Vidyalankar1975\">{{cite book |last=Vidyalankar |first= Nardev|authorlink= |author2=Manohar Somera |title= Arya Samaj and Indians abroad|year=1975 |publisher=Sarvadeshik Arya Pratinidhi Sabha |location= New Delhi, India|isbn= | page = 125}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n[[Arya Samaj in Fiji]]\n\n==References==\n<!-- this 'empty' section displays references defined elsewhere -->\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sharma, Shri Krishna}}\n[[Category:Indian emigrants to Fiji]]\n[[Category:Indian Hindu missionaries]]\n[[Category:Arya Samajis in Fiji]]\n[[Category:Hindu missionaries]]\n[[Category:Fijian Hindus]]\n\n\n{{Fiji-bio-stub}}\n{{Hindu-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=October 2016}}\n'''[[Pandit]] Shri Krishna Sharma''' was an [[Arya Samaj]] preacher who came to [[Fiji]] in 1926 from [[Rajkot]], [[India]]. He was a gifted public speaker and singer of religious songs. He provided impetus to the Arya Samaj movement in Fiji. Under his influence Arya Samaj schools and temples were established in Fiji. He was responsible for the establishment of the ''[[Hindu Maha Sabha (Fiji)|Hindu Maha Sabha]]'' for the purpose of uniting all [[Hindus]] in Fiji. He advocated ''[[shuddhi]]'' (reconversion to Hinduism) and this caused conflict with [[Muslim]]s and [[Christians]] in Fiji.\n\nSharma also started a monthly Hindi language newspaper called the ''Vedic Sandesh''.<ref name=\"Kanwal1980\">{{cite book |last=Kanwal |first=J. S. |authorlink= |title=A Hundred years of Hindi in Fiji  |year=1980 |publisher=Fiji Teachers Union |location=Suva, Fiji |isbn=| page= 92 }}</ref>\n\nHe returned to India in 1929 and the Government of Fiji refused permission for him to return to Fiji.\n\nIn 1956, he returned to Fiji to participate in the [[Golden Jubilee]] of the Arya Samaj in Fiji. He founded the [[Dayanand Anglo-Vedic Schools System|D.A.V. College]] in [[Suva]] and an Arya temple in [[Nadi]].<ref name=\"Vidyalankar1975\">{{cite book |last=Vidyalankar |first= Nardev|authorlink= |author2=Manohar Somera |title= Arya Samaj and Indians abroad|year=1975 |publisher=Sarvadeshik Arya Pratinidhi Sabha |location= New Delhi, India|isbn= | page = 125}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n[[Arya Samaj in Fiji]]\n\n==References==\n<!-- this 'empty' section displays references defined elsewhere -->\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sharma, Shri Krishna}}\n[[Category:Indian emigrants to Fiji]]\n[[Category:Indian Hindu missionaries]]\n[[Category:Arya Samajis in Fiji]]\n[[Category:Hindu missionaries]]\n[[Category:Fijian Hindus]]\n\n\n{{Fiji-bio-stub}}\n{{Hindu-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shri_Krishna_Sharma"}
{"title_page": "Sheikh Ubaidullah", "text_new": "{{short description|Muslim Arab saint, b, 640AD}}\n'''Shiekh Ubaidullah''' (born c. 640 AD) was a Muslim Arab [[saint]] in [[Medina]]. He was the grandson of [[Abu Bakr]] from whom Ubaidullah learnt about [[Islam]] in an environment free from desire and greed of [[materialism]] for developing his moral and spiritual beliefs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tnaexcursions.com/indiatour/south-india/lakshadweep/lakshadweep-city|title=Lakshadweep Tourism {{!}} Best of Lakshadweep, India : Time & Again Excursions|website=www.tnaexcursions.com|access-date=2019-09-07}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=education|first=Study IQ|title=Genetic study of Lakshadweep people, Know interesting facts about its Islands, Current Affairs 2019|url=https://trkeys.net/watch/_kVXrtfCfzs-genetic-study-of-lakshadweep-people-know-interesting-facts-about-its-islands-current-affairs-2019.html|language=tr|access-date=2019-09-07}}</ref>\n{{Islam}}\n\n== Early life ==\nThe name Ubaidullah is an indirect [[Quranic]] name that means \u201clittle servant of Allah\u201d. ''Ubaidullah'' is the diminutive form of the name ''Abdullah'' and is formed from ''Ubaid'' (\u201clittle servant\u201d), ''-u-'' (\u201cof\u201d) and ''Allah'' (\u201cGod\u201d).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://quranicnames.com/ubaidullah/|title=Ubaidullah - Islamic Name Meaning - Baby Names for Muslims|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-07}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nAccording to [[tradition]] Sheikh Ubaidullah was once praying in a mosque in [[Mecca]] where he felt asleep and saw a dream in which he was told by the prophet Muhammad to go to distant lands from the east of Jeddah to preach Islam.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://lakshadweep.gov.in/about-lakshadweep/history/|title=History &#124; Lakshadweep &#124; India}}</ref>\n\nHe interpreted the dream as a [[divine]] vision from [[Allah]] for his salvation and the people of those distant lands, so he proceeded to [[Jeddah]] where from he traveled across the ocean for accomplishing his mission.\n\nOn his journey his vessel capsized in a storm and he had to continue his journey by drifting on a plank till he reached [[Amini, India|Amini]] in AH 41 (663 AD). He started his act of preaching from Amini and was able to convert the Pondambelli family despite the initial linguistic challenges. After facing opposition there he left Amini with some of his new Muslim fellows and moved to [[Andrott]] where he got significantly high conversions. He then went to [[Kavaratti|Kawaratti]] and [[Agatti]], preaching there and then came back to Amini. This time unlike his first arrival in Amini, he was welcomed and  via his preaching could successfully influence and convert almost the whole of population to Islam. At last stage of his life, he travelled to [[Andrott]] where he lived the rest of his life preaching and teaching. Ubaidullah never went back to his home land of Hijaz and devoted his life for [[dawah]].<ref name=\"auto\" />\n\nSheikh Ubaidullah advanced Islam in [[Lakshadweep]] (now in India) Islands by delivering sermons before the islanders. Apparently, the saint died at Andrott Island with his remains buried in Jumah Mosque. His grave is revered by people as sacred.{{citation needed|date=September 2019}} His work was rewarded as 97% of Islanders are Muslims at present.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.indstu.com/Lakshadweep.html|title=Lakshadweep|website=www.indstu.com|access-date=2019-09-06}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Muslim saints]]\n[[Category:600s births]]\n[[Category:Year of death unknown]]\n[[Category:Muslim missionaries]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Muslim Arab saint, b, 640AD}}\n'''Shiekh Ubaidullah''' (born c. 640 AD) was a Muslim Arab [[saint]] in [[Medina]]. He was the grandson of [[Abu Bakr]] from whom Ubaidullah learnt about [[Islam]] in an environment free from desire and greed of [[materialism]] for developing his moral and spiritual beliefs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tnaexcursions.com/indiatour/south-india/lakshadweep/lakshadweep-city|title=Lakshadweep Tourism {{!}} Best of Lakshadweep, India : Time & Again Excursions|website=www.tnaexcursions.com|access-date=2019-09-07}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=education|first=Study IQ|title=Genetic study of Lakshadweep people, Know interesting facts about its Islands, Current Affairs 2019|url=https://trkeys.net/watch/_kVXrtfCfzs-genetic-study-of-lakshadweep-people-know-interesting-facts-about-its-islands-current-affairs-2019.html|language=tr|access-date=2019-09-07}}</ref>\n{{Islam}}\n\n== Early life ==\nThe name Ubaidullah is an indirect [[Quranic]] name that means \u201clittle servant of Allah\u201d. ''Ubaidullah'' is the diminutive form of the name ''Abdullah'' and is formed from ''Ubaid'' (\u201clittle servant\u201d), ''-u-'' (\u201cof\u201d) and ''Allah'' (\u201cGod\u201d).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://quranicnames.com/ubaidullah/|title=Ubaidullah - Islamic Name Meaning - Baby Names for Muslims|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-07}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nAccording to [[tradition]] Sheikh Ubaidullah was once praying in a mosque in [[Mecca]] where he felt asleep and saw a dream in which he was told by the prophet Muhammad to go to distant lands from the east of Jeddah to preach Islam.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://lakshadweep.gov.in/about-lakshadweep/history/|title=History &#124; Lakshadweep &#124; India}}</ref> \n\nHe interpreted the dream as a [[divine]] vision from [[Allah]] for his salvation and the people of those distant lands, so he proceeded to [[Jeddah]] where from he traveled across the ocean for accomplishing his mission. \n\nOn his journey his vessel capsized in a storm and he had to continue his journey by drifting on a plank till he reached [[Amini, India|Amini]] in AH 41 (663 AD). He started his act of preaching from Amini and was able to convert the Pondambelli family despite the initial linguistic challenges. After facing opposition there he left Amini with some of his new Muslim fellows and moved to [[Andrott]] where he got significantly high conversions. He then went to [[Kavaratti|Kawaratti]] and [[Agatti]], preaching there and then came back to Amini. This time unlike his first arrival in Amini, he was welcomed and  via his preaching could successfully influence and convert almost the whole of population to Islam. At last stage of his life, he travelled to [[Andrott]] where he lived the rest of his life preaching and teaching. Ubaidullah never went back to his home land of Hijaz and devoted his life for [[Dawah|dawah.]]<ref name=\"auto\" /> \n\nSheikh Ubaidullah advanced Islam in [[Lakshadweep]] (now in India) Islands by delivering sermons before the islanders. Apparently, the saint died at Andrott Island with his remains buried in Jumah Mosque. His grave is revered by people as sacred.{{citation needed|date=September 2019}} His work was rewarded as 97% of Islanders are Muslims at present.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.indstu.com/Lakshadweep.html|title=Lakshadweep|website=www.indstu.com|access-date=2019-09-06}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n[[Category:Muslim saints]]\n[[Category:600s births]]\n[[Category:Year of death unknown]]\n[[Category:Muslim_missionaries]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sheikh_Ubaidullah"}
